<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Bring Record High Water Levels On Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Water levels on the middle and
lower reaches of China's Yangtze River have been above the warning
line, and at record highs in some places, according to the State
Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The river began to rise in June at the beginning of the flood
season, and frequent torrential rains in southern China recently
have brought the water level on the middle and lower reaches of
the river up. In some places, the amount of precipitation has been
more than 1 meter.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains have caused flooding on the Xinjiang, Fujiang and
Changjiang rivers in central China in Hubei Province, and around
Dongting Lake in nearby Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Water levels on the Yangtze's main stream, which has taken
water from its branches, is also rising dramatically, with areas
from Yichang in Hubei to Nanjing in Jiangsu reporting water above
the danger line by July 2.
</P>
<P>
Water levels on the middle and lower reaches of the river where
flooding is at its worst are at record highs for the '90s.
</P>
<P>
Almost 2 million local people and soldiers in Hubei, Hunan,
Jiangxi, Anhui and Jiangsu provinces have been working on dams and
dikes in flood areas and have reinforced more than 240 places
where dikes and dams have been breached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
