<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK's New Airport Runs Smoothly on 1st Day (2) (By Wang Qun and Chang Kefei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new airport was scheduled to handle about 450 flights, and
70,000 to 80,000 passengers on the first day.
</P>
<P>
But during the first few hours of operation, there were
problems with the baggage handling system, the flight information
display system, and even the escalators. The airport authorities
has already tackled some of the issues, and is dealing with the
rest.
</P>
<P>
Leeks said: "It's a good, positive sign that we're identifying
problems. That's all part of the challenge of running one of the
world's great modern international airports."
</P>
<P>
Gong Wang Yang, a young Philippine man flying in with his
family from Manila before noon, was satisfied with the speed of
baggage reclaiming.
</P>
<P>
"As we arrived at the baggage reclaiming area, our pieces of
baggage were already on the carousel," he said. Packing a dozen
pieces of luggage on two handcarts, Gong said the handcart was
easy to use.
</P>
<P>
At the departures hall, "Ask Me" ambassadors, all played by
college students, were helping passengers in need, replying to
their inquires, guiding them to check-in counters and the post
office where they could buy commemorative stamps.
</P>
<P>
Their work complemented information desks, sign-posting and
information kiosks that display information at one's fingertips.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 retail outlets in the terminal building opened
for business Monday, selling fast-food, books and magazines, and
souvenirs to passengers and sightseers, who queued up to grab up
some commemorative items.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds and thousands of Hong Kong people flooded to one of
the world's most spacious buildings to catch a first glimpse of
the brand new airport on its opening day.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong had gotten a fully operational airport at Chek Lap
Kok by 6:30 a.m. Monday, about six hours after all lights along
the 3,390-meter-long runway at the old Kai Tak airport were
switched off to end its 73-year-old services.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the new airport was backed by a successful
overnight relocation of the most critical airport equipment and
facilities from the old Kai Tak Airport. Over the 13 hours of work
up to 6:30 a.m. Monday, there were more than 1,100 vehicle
movements by land, sea and air, including 14 barge and 31 aircraft
movements.
</P>
<P>
"The overnight relocation went superbly," Leeks told reporters,
adding "many of the movements were ahead of schedule."
</P>
<P>
An integrated public transport network set forth for new Hong
Kong International Airport went into full operation Monday,
including railway, bus, taxi and ferry services.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Express, a railway built specially to carry
passengers between the central business district on Hong Kong
Island and the new airport in 23 minutes, commenced operation at
5:00 a.m., one hour earlier than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Built on a 1,248-hectare reclaimed island, the new airport is
part of the Airport Core Program, a series of 10 projects that
cost a total of 20 billion U.S. dollars. The airport took eight
years to finish and will cater for the aviation needs into the
next century.
</P>
<P>
At its opening, the new airport is able to handle 35 million
passengers and 3 million tons of cargo annually; ultimately, it is
capable of handling 87 million passengers and 9 million tons of
cargo. A second runway will be completed by the end of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
