<HEADLINE> Syrian President to Visit France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad will
pay a state visit to France from July 16 to 17, said French
officials on Monday.
</P>
<P>
This visit is in response to an official invitation offered by
President Jacques Chirac on May 24, and will be the first visit to
France by Assad since 1976.
</P>
<P>
The visit also comes at a time when the Middle East peace
process remains deadlocked while Syrian-Israeli peace talks have
been suspended since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Assad is expected to discuss with President Jacques Chirac and
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on ways to re-open the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Both France and Syria regard the situation in the Middle East
as dangerous, and have been maintaining permanent contacts and
consultation over the issue.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have improved their relations since President
Chirac took office in 1995 after a difficult time in the 1980s
because of Syria's intervention in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said recently that they were enjoying a "most positive
period" and French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine described
bilateral relations as a "strategic partnership". 
</P>
</TEXT>
