<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Defense Minister to Visit Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Defense Minister Yiannakis
Omirou will start a four-day visit to Russia on Tuesday for talks
with his counterpart Igor Sergeyev on military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Monday, Omirou said he
will discuss in Moscow issues of mutual interest in the light of
an existing agreement for military and technical cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It was announced that Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides will
also pay a four-day visit to Moscow from July 11 at the invitation
of Moscow Mayor Yuri Ruskov as a guest of honor at the World
Youth Games, to be held in the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Moscow, Clerides is expected to meet Russian
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the two Cypriot leaders' visits to Russia were related
to Cyprus' purchase of Russian missiles which has led to tension
on the divided island, Cypriot government spokesman Christos
Stylianides said at his press briefing here that it was clear that
the Cypriot government did not intend to create tension itself.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered the Russian-made S-300
surface-to-air missile system in 1997 in a bid to boost its air
defense. The missiles were scheduled for delivery in
mid-August. This controversial deal has triggered warnings from
rival Turkish Cypriots and Turkey, which threatened to take "all
necessary measures" to prevent the deployment of the system.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides pointed out that Clerides would visit Moscow at the
invitation of the city mayor, while Omirou's visit is related to a
cooperation agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Ambassador to Cyprus Georgi Mouradov was
quoted as saying Monday that the Russian missile system was only a
defensive weapon that would have no harm to the Turkish Cypriots
or Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He told the Turkish Cypriot newspaper "Kibris" that the S-300
missiles would only be used in case of an air raid.
</P>
<P>
Asked what stance Russia would take in case of a war in Cyprus
over the missile dispute, Mouradov ruled out such possibility,
saying neither the Cypriots, nor Greece or Turkey wanted a war.
</P>
<P>
He added that he did not believe Turkey would launch strike
against the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in the
aftermath of a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has kept 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus, which was
declared unilaterally in 1983 by Turkish Cypriots as a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" that has been only
recognized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
