<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK on Course for Mini-Recession: Surveys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Three surveys have revealed a slump
in economic confidence among Britain's businessmen, fueling fears
that Britain is now on course for a "mini-recession."
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Directors (IOD), the Center for Economic and
Business Research (CEBR) and the London Chamber of Commerce have
all found evidence of a growing pessimism.
</P>
<P>
The CEBR's report warned that the UK economy is "uncomfortably
close to stagnation. In its latest quarterly economic forecasts,
the research institute said, "Rising wage pressure, combined with
an excessively strong exchange rate and wilting manufacturing
output, has heightened the risk of a mini-recession in 1999."
</P>
<P>
The CEBR's central forecast was that economic growth will slow
from 3.1 percent last year to 1.6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Growth in 1999 will average 1.8 percent, it said, while
unemployment will rise from 1.36 million this year to more than
1.5 million in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The institute also predicted the underlying inflation rate will
stay above 3 percent for the rest of the year, and that interest
rates will be above 8 percent by the year end.
</P>
<P>
Tim Melville-Ross, director general of the IOD, said at the
weekend that businessmen are becoming increasingly depressed by
the impact of the financial crisis in Southeast Asia and
successive rises in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
He told GMTV's program, "The degree of the fall in optimism
about the state of the economy generally is quite marked." He said
that a further interest rate rise by the Bank of England's
monetary Policy Committee (MPC) later this week will be "perverse
in the extreme" as the rates are already too high.
</P>
<P>
The London Chamber of Commerce's quarterly survey revealed that
service sector exports have fallen to the lowest level since 1991,
and 81 percent of businessmen want a weaker pound to revive
exports.
</P>
<P>
However, although there is growing evidence of a slowdown in
economic activity in Britain, wages and prices are still rising.
</P>
<P>
Because of this, many observers in the City fear that the MPC,
in its attempt to bring the underlying rate of UK inflation back
to the 2.5 percent target, will raise rates again, despite the
damage this will do to economic prospects.
</P>
<P>
Many economists believe the UK economy is on the brink of a
painful period of `stagflation' -- a combination of weak economic
growth with rising inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
