<HEADLINE> World's Chip Sales Slump Despite of Price Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Semiconductor sales worldwide in
May fell by nearly 13 percent from the year-earlier period to 9.99
billion U.S. dollars, the lowest monthly sales level since
February 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal reported Monday that the downturn,
which has spread to nearly every category of chip maker and their
equipment suppliers, was brought by problems in Asia and pricing
pressures caused by low-cost personal computers.
</P>
<P>
The Semiconductor Industry Association and market researchers
Pathfinder Research Inc. and VLSI Research Inc. predict decreases
in different levels. Some analysts don't foresee much growth until
2000.
</P>
<P>
Silicon Valley companies have either laid off workers or issued
warnings about second-quarter results, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Even mighty Intel Corp., despite its near monopoly on the
computing engines for PCs, has projected a flat second quarter and
lower profit margins. The company, hurt by falling prices on its
microprocessor chips, said last week that it would shut two
manufacturing plants in Oregon for eight days to help reduce
inventory of older chips and temporarily idle 1,700 workers.
</P>
<P>
The DRAM market, which deals with the memory chips of PCs, is
also being squeezed fast. Manufacturers in Taiwan pushed prices
down even faster, the paper said. Chips that cost three U.S.
dollars at the beginning of the year now sell for less than two
U.S. dollars. More factories are losing money while the market
prices are bellow their production costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
