<HEADLINE> Western French City of Nante Develops Tramway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The western French city of Nante will
expand its tramway network to promote public transport and reduce
pollution from waste of private cars, said city officials Monday.
</P>
<P>
The city, which is called "Venise of the West" because of its
numerous canals, launched its first tramway line in 1985 and now
has two lines covering 27 kilometers and serving 160,000
commuters.
</P>
<P>
Once a new line is staged from 2002 to 2005, Nante will have 46
kilometers of tramways.
</P>
<P>
The city's Socialist mayor and National Assembly deputy
Jean-Marc Ayrault said that the construction of the new tramway
line is not only for transport, but also for giving "a new breath"
to the city and attracting tourists.
</P>
<P>
An investigation shows that 92 percent of the city's
inhabitants are happy with tramway as their means for moving
around.
</P>
<P>
The number of cars in the city has dropped by nearly 60 percent
since 1994 because of the tramways.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government is also considering renovating the
city's old train railways to link them with the tramways.
</P>
<P>
Once these old trains are again put into use, Nante will have a
85 kilometer public transport network, said officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
