<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Urges Action After "Kosovo Liberation Army" Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- France on Monday called for
international action to prevent the Kosovo conflict spreading
after the Kosovo Liberation Army (UCK) took control of over 40
percent of the territory of the Serbian southern province.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis has changed nature with the taking by the Kosovo
Liberation Army of 40 percent of the territory," said French
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Secret-Gazeau.
</P>
<P>
Paris expected "energetic and immediate action" by the
international community, said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people, including many women, children and the
elderly, have died in clashes raging since February between Serb
forces and ethnic Albanians majority seeking independence from
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
While reiterating warnings of possible western military
intervention in Kosovo, the spokeswoman stopped short of backing
independence.
</P>
<P>
France supported autonomy for the Serb province where ethnic
Albanians outnumber Serbs nine to one.
</P>
<P>
NATO's military committee was meeting in Brussels on Monday,
and the Contact Group of Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Russia
and the United States will gather in Bonn to discuss latest
developments in the Kosovo situation on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
France also regards Kosovo's ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim
Rugova as the "central negotiator" representing Albanians in talks
with the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said contacts with the UCK were not ruled out
if they could help stop violence.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Germany have called for participation of
the UCK in Kosovo talks, but Belgrade has refused as it regards
the UCK as a terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavian authorities have strongly opposed any external
interference in Kosovo, which it views as a domestic issue, and
also rejected the idea of independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
