<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Upbeat About Re-Election Despite Unfavorable Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- With an eye on the improving economy,
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Monday expressed confidence about
winning re-election in the September elections despite the poor
showings of his ruling party in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before travelling to an Austrian spa for his
traditional summer vacation, Kohl repeated government projections
that the economy would grow at a rate of close to three percent
this year while unemployment would fall below four million this
autumn.
</P>
<P>
The structural reforms introduced by the government had
contributed to the economic upswing, Kohl stressed.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, whose Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party is trailing
almost ten percentage points behind the main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) in the polls, admitted that the SPD had
done more to mobilize voters than his CDU party.
</P>
<P>
But he said that with less than three months left before the
September elections, about three quarters of German voters had not
yet made up their minds and still open to supporting the CDU.
</P>
<P>
"We have not actually started our election campaign," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
The September 27 general elections put Kohl against his much
younger SPD challenger Gerhard Schroeder, who is the premier of
the western Lower Saxony state.
</P>
<P>
Kohl stressed that the upcoming election campaign would see a
serious comparison of the actual policies pursued by the CDU and
the SPD, not rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
"We can seize our chances, and we will win the election," Kohl
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
