<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Boxer Accused of Hitting Two Cops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Former welterweight champion
Charles Murray was arrested Sunday after punching two police
officers in a street brawl in Rochester, New York.
</P>
<P>
Murray, 29, was charged with second-degree assault of a police
officer. It was his fourth arrest in four years.
</P>
<P>
Police arrived on the scene to break up a fight involving more
than 150 people. The first officers tried to disperse the fight
using pepper spray.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said Murray was trying to break up the fight, too,
but he was struck on the head with a nightstick by an officer.
Murray punched two officers after that. One officer was treated
for facial injuries at hospital, the other didn't need medical
care.
</P>
<P>
Murray was treated for a cut on his head. He was held without
bail Sunday night until his arraignment.
</P>
<P>
Murray won the IBF welterweight title in 1993, but hasn't had a
professional bout since 1997. His career record was 40-5 with 23
knockouts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
