<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Status of African Franc in Euro Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) Monday
approved the status of the African franc within the zone of the
future European single currency, announced French Minister of
Finance and Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn.
</P>
<P>
The 15 EU countries reached a political agreement in Brussels
on the status of the African franc, also called CFA franc, which
is used in a dozen French-speaking African countries whose
currency is pegged to the French franc on a 1-100 exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is based on a report by the European Commission
presented in July and will be subjected to approval by the
Frankfurt-based European Central Bank, said Strauss-Kahn.
</P>
<P>
Only a change of the nature of financial agreement between
France and the CFA franc countries or an enlargement of the CFA
franc zone to other countries needs the approval of the other 14
EU members, said the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn estimated that the CFA franc countries would be
guaranteed of their financial status by the EU agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
