<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Accuses Netanyahu of Losing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition leader Ehud
Barak launched an attack Monday against Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, accusing him of losing credibility both at home and
abroad due to his damage to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The war of words was fought in a heated debate between the two
political rivals in a special session of the Knesset (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
Barak, head of the Labor Party, slammed Netanyahu for leading
Israel to "an all-out confrontation." He warned that the total
impasse in the peace process would cause a "certain explosion" in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Reciting a list of foreign leaders that had been fed up with
Netanyahu's policies, Barak said Netanyahu was totally isolated in
the international arena and had destroyed the prestige that Israel
once enjoyed during the rule of the previous Labor government.
</P>
<P>
The list included such big names as Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, U.S. President Bill Clinton, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Jordanian
King Hussein. The leaders had all refused to talk to Netanyahu,
Barak notedd.
</P>
<P>
Barak went further to point out that Netanyahu had even lost
credibility among his coalition. He cited the division between
Netanyahu and some Cabinet ministers over his handling of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
For example, Barak said, National Infrastructure Minister Ariel
Sharon doubted the arrangement Netanyahu made with the Palestinians
on ending the military standoff in Gaza Strip last week.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told the Sunday Cabinet session that he was glad with
the arrangement. But Sharon told other ministers that Netanyahu
complained to him on Friday that he had not been informed of the
terms of the arrangement and he was not pleased with the settlement.
</P>
<P>
The dispute has demonstrated that "even his own ministers
do not believe him," Barak said.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Netanyahu stressed that the opposition should
support the government at "the crucial time" in the
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"I would expect the opposition leader to stand with the
government of Israel to demand the Palestinians live up to their
obligations," he said. He reiterated the responsibility for the
long deadlock in the peace process rested on the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Likud Knesset members came to Netanyahu's aid by accusing the
Labor of launching an incitement campaign against the prime
minister. But in quick response, Labor Secretary-General Raanan
Cohen retorted that Likud members, who he said had incited against
the slain Labor prime minister Yitzhak Rabin, "should be the last
ones to talk about incitement."
</P>
<P>
The Monday special Knesset session was demanded by the Labor,
which gathered 40 lawmakers' signatures needed to convene such a
session, to request Netanyahu to make a policy statement to the
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
