<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Parliamentarians Vote to Change Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- French parliamentarians from both the
National Assembly and the Senate vote with a crushing majority to
approve the amendment of the French Constitution to allow the
overseas territory of New Caledonia to change its status prior to
gaining a possible full independence.
</P>
<P>
Among the 885 parliamentarians attending a joint session of the
two chambers of parliament in Versaille south of Paris, 827 voted
for the revision of the constitution, said National Assembly
speaker Laurent Fabius.
</P>
<P>
This was far more than the 515 votes, or those of three fifths
of the parliamentarians, needed for approving constitutional
amendments.
</P>
<P>
This is the ninth amendment of the French Constitution under
the Fifth Republic since 1958.
</P>
<P>
The French government and the pro-independence and pro-French
parties of New Caledonia signed an agreement on May 5 on the
future of the South Pacific archipelago.
</P>
<P>
The agreement allows New Caledonia to gain full administrative
autonomy in 15 to 20 years before deciding whether to choose
independence or not through a referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
