<HEADLINE> Waigel Sees Sharp Cut in German Budget Deficit by 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
has presented a fiscal plan envisaging a nearly balanced budget by
the year 2002, German press reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget plan which is due to go before the German
cabinet for approval Wednesday, Germany's budget deficit would be
reduced to 2 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) in 1999
and to 0.5 percent by 2002, Waigel was quoted by German media as
saying at a meeting of European Union finance ministers in
Brussels Monday.
</P>
<P>
Waigel's plan envisaged a total 1999 German budget of 465.3
billion marks (255 billion U.S. dollars), up just 0.4 percent from
the 1998 level.
</P>
<P>
The planned budget deficit would be cut from 56.4 billion marks
(31 billion dollars) in 1998 to 56.2 billion marks (30.9 billion
dollars) in 1999 and to 45.3 billion marks (24.9 billion dollars)
by 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
