<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Nations Suffer Most from Asian Crisis: U.N. Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Poor and vulnerable nations
suffer first and most as a consequence of the Asian economic
crisis and the international community should give them a hand,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Opening a high-level session of the U.N. Economic and Social
Council, Annan said developing countries are less able than
developed nations to withstand the fallout of the Asian crisis,
and even countries far removed from the Asian region are feeling
the impact.
</P>
<P>
African countries, he said, are experiencing collateral damage
in the form of reduced commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
"International cooperation must focus first on these nations:
on who do not have effective lobbying groups or whose voices are
otherwise not heard," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dealing with the impact of globalization on developing
countries, the secretary-general said the needs of Africa and the
least developed countries should be focused.
</P>
<P>
He urged the abolishment of non-tariff barriers facing these
nations, duty-free treatment of their exports and relief of their
unsustainable debt burdens.
</P>
<P>
He saw it "unacceptable" that official development assistance
by developed countries has fallen to its lowest point in history
when it is needed most.
</P>
<P>
The three-day session, featured by participation of leading
international trade and finance institutions and trade ministers,
is mainly devoted to finding ways of overcoming the impact of the
Asian crisis on world trade.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. survey shows that growth in dollar value of world
exports is expected to fall to roughly 2.5 percent in 1998 from
4.3 percent in 1996 and 2.7 percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
