<HEADLINE> N.Irish Panel Gives Go-Ahead for Orange Marches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's independent
Parades Commission Monday gave the Orangemen the go-ahead to march
through the nationalist Lower Ormeau Road area of Belfast next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Commission chairman Alistair Graham said the decision was not a
"trade-off" for its block on Orangemen in Drumcree, Portadown.
</P>
<P>
The stand-off between 5,000 Protestant Orangemen and police has
continued since Sunday afternoon in the town of Portadown over the
security forces' determination to enforce the panel's ruling
barring them from walking down the mainly Catholic Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
Graham said the controversial parade in Belfast would be
allowed to go ahead on condition that the marchers pass the
contentious part of the Lower Ormeau Road by 8.30 a.m. (0730 GMT)
and that the Orange Order's pipe and drums bands stay silent.
</P>
<P>
"This was a difficult decision, but I'm sure we've arrived at
the right one," Graham said in Belfast. "We hope that this
decision will be respected by all parties."
</P>
<P>
But the Catholic residents in the Lower Ormeau Roan area
objected the ruling and pledged to fight the decision by seeking a
judicial review. 
</P>
