<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New U.N. Envoy in Cyprus Assumes Duties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The new chief of Mission of the
U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) Dame Ann Hercus
assumed her duties here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hercus, a New Zealander and also deputy special representative
for Cyprus of the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, arrived here
last week to replace Gustave Feissel, who retired after 15-year
service in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference Monday, Hercus said she will do her best
to help the Greek and Turkish Cypriots to reach a settlement over
their disputes "within the existing U.N. framework."
</P>
<P>
"I am here to listen to the two leaders, to offer a new U.N.
perspective from time to time and follow through on initiatives,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Annan has reaffirmed to her "his determination to pursue
intensified efforts to bring about a comprehensive settlement to
the Cyprus problem," Hercus said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into a Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
landed troops and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Ever since, the 1,200-personnel UNFICYP has been patrolling
along the 180-kilometer-long buffer zone across the Mediterranean
island.
</P>
<P>
Praising the work done so far by the UNFICYP, Hercus said that
peace-keeping and peace-making are complementary.
</P>
<P>
"Peace-keeping involves international troops, peace-making
offers people and their leaders a door, a bridge, a room where
lasting peace can be brokered," she said.
</P>
<P>
Hercus was permanent representative of New Zealand in the
United Nations from 1988-1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Accepts Netanyahu's Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (Parliament)
Monday accepted the policy statement made by Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu over the peace talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The statement was passed in a vote of 43 to 42 after a heated
debate, in which the opposition attacked Netanyahu's policies in
dealing with the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Monday's special session was convened at the request of the
leading opposition Labor Party, whose leader Ehud Barak strongly
accused Netanyahu of leading the nation to an all-out war.
</P>
<P>
In his policy statement, Netanyahu reiterated that it was the
Palestinians that should be responsible for the 16-month long
deadlock in the peace talks because they had failed to fulfill
their commitments to the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu demanded the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
take real actions to implement its obligations, including ending
incitement against Israel, detaining terrorists, collecting
illegal arms and outlawing terror organizations.
</P>
<P>
He said that that if the PNA accepted the principle of
reciprocity and fulfilled its commitments, then a breakthrough in
the peace talks would be achieved in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Noting that his insistence on security might not be popular,
Netanyahu promised that he would adhere to his stance in the talks
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Despite the scathing attack against him, Netanyahu urged the
opposition to support him in the peace negotiations in order to
keep Israel's security interests.
</P>
<P>
This was the first policy statement made by Netanyahu to the
Knesset in seven months. The opposition has complained that the
prime minister was boycotting the parliament by refusing to make
any policy statement since last December.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled for 16
months since Netanyahu government started building a Jewish
settlement in a controversial site of East Jerusalem in March
last year. The current sticking point is the Israeli refusal to
accept an American initiative for a 13 percent withdrawal in the
next Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Warning that the deadlock in the peace process could ignite
violence in the region, PNA President Yasser Arafat has been
making efforts to solicit international pressure to press Israel to
carry out the long overdue troop redeployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
