<HEADLINE> Kabila, Mugabe Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
and his Democratic Congolese counterpart Laurent Desire Kabila
Monday held private talks for more than three hours here on
COMESA and security issues.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who arrived here Monday morning, told the Zimbabwe
News Agency Ziana that the talks centered on the Common Market
for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) of which he is the
current chairman.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the talks, however, said discussions included
security issues, Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said it would take his country some time to reconstruct
its economy which was plundered by the late president Mobutu Sese
Seko.
</P>
<P>
"Reconstruction is a very long program," he said, adding, "We
are doing well in all things. The rebuilding exercise for our
military is going on very well, and people are happy."
</P>
<P>
On whether the donor community was forthcoming in helping the
central African country to rebuild, Kabila said, "In Congo it is
our policy to first count on our own efforts and what belongs to
us before we look for outside help."
</P>
<P>
Last week there was a shooting incident outside the
presidential villa in the capital Kinshasa, which Kabila
described as "not very serious."
</P>
<P>
"That was just a small incident. It was not very serious. It
happens in other countries, even in Washington," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila was evasive when questioned about the circumstances
surrounding the release of opposition leader Ettienne Tshisekedi,
who spent months in his rural home after an imposed internal
exile.
</P>
<P>
"Why do you want to talk much about individuals?" asked
Kabila. "There are many Congolese. Why only someone who was used
by the imperialists?"
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who was accompanied by Justice Minister Mwenze
Kongolo, left for home soon after the talks at a local hotel.
</P>
