<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Delegation on AIDS Off to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean delegation left the
country's second largest city Bulawayo Monday for a week-long
stay in Uganda in a bid to learn how the east African country is
coping with HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
A UNICEF spokesperson said the trip would expose the
delegation to strategies being taken in Uganda to curb the spread
of HIV/AIDS, and how infected people are being supported, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is one of the countries in Africa which is succeeding
in combating the spread of incurable HIV/AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The trip was organized by the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) in conjunction with Zimbabwe's ruling ZANU (PF) party,
National AIDS Control Program and United Nation AIDS Development
Services.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is second to Botswana on the world list of countries
worst affected by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
About 1.4 million adults, 25.8 percent of sexually active
adults between 15 and 49 years are thought to be infected with
HIV. Of these 720,000 are women.
</P>
<P>
More than 700 people die every week from HIV/AIDS related
illnesses in the country. 
</P>
