<HEADLINE> Regional Workshop on Education Opens in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A two-week sub-regional workshop on
strengthening national education statistical information systems
(NESIS) started in Harare Monday.
</P>
<P>
Opening the workshop, Zimbabwe's Education and Culture
Minister Gabriel Machinga said the inception of NESIS in 1991 had
revitalized statistical systems in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The importance of up to date information for effective policy
formulation in the education system cannot be over emphasized as
we strive toward achieving education for all by the next
millennium," he said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop organized by the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) and United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) is being attended by 36 representatives
from 17 English speaking countries in the sub-Saharan region.
</P>
<P>
The workshop will focus on capacity building through the
development of a network of African training institutions
necessary for building self-sustenance and policies relevant in
various regions.
</P>
<P>
It will also launch regional and national action plans for the
end of decade assessment.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is expected to build regional capacity programs,
projects, work-plans and partnerships for the network of African
institutions. 
</P>
