<HEADLINE> Iran's Dependence on Oil Urged to Be Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Majlis Speaker Nateq Nouri
Monday called for efforts to reduce the country's dependence on
oil, saying that the country's single-product economy has become a
serious matter of concern.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the fourth power industry fair, Nouri said
sustainable development cannot be based on shaky foundations such
as oil.
</P>
<P>
He said the conversion of oil into a political tool in the
hands of "arrogant powers," the impact of economic crises on oil
prices and the fact that oil consumption is not confined to one
generation alone have turned oil into an unstable base for
development.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Nouri stressed
that "the country's independence can be guaranteed only when we
can stand on our own feet and can diminish reliance on oil."
</P>
<P>
All impediments to the expansion of non-oil exports should be
lifted, he said, terming skilled manpower and production as the
most important key to development.
</P>
<P>
Heavily hit by lower-than-expected oil prices, Iranian
government has pledged to transform the country's oil economy to
one less dependent on oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
President Mohammad Khatami is expected to announce a package
of economic reforms in the near future to inject new life to the
country's ailing economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
