<HEADLINE> Iran Stresses Equal Rights in Exploiting Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Monday urged that a legal regime on the Caspian Sea be determined
in the interests of all littoral states to ensure their fair
exploitation of the sea's resources.
</P>
<P>
Khatami made the call in talks with visiting Turkmen President
Saparmurat Niyazov, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
His words in response to a recent report that some Caspian
states are seeking to divide the world's largest inland water, a
move Tehran is bitterly opposed.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been emphasizing the "equal rights" of Caspian states
to exploit sea resources instead of a division, by which it feared
its maneuvering space will be largely limited for its relatively
short coastal line, as compared with the other four littoral
states - Russia, Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkmen President Niyazov also stressed the need for
an immediate approval of the legal regime honoring the interests
of all the littoral states.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Iranian-Turkmen ties, Khatami said that Iran and
Turkmenistan have excellent cooperation in boosting progress of
the two countries, and seeking peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov, who arrived here Monday morning on a three-day visit,
also voiced his satisfaction with the growing cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that the set-up over 80 Iranian firms in Turkmenistan
indicated a growth in economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The building of railway linking the two countries showed their
determination to develop their economic and industrial
cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also agreed to establish six committees on
oil and gas, commerce, health, transport and telecommunications,
finance and banking, and energy, to study and coordinate bilateral
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
