<HEADLINE> U.N. Secretary-General to Visit Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan will visit Brazil, Uruguay, Argentina, Guatemala and Mexico
starting on July 13, the U.N. spokesman's office announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Brasilia, Brazil, the secretary-general will meet with
President Fernando Henrique Cardozo, visit the parliament and
deliver an address before the Diplomatic Academy of Brazil at the
Foreign Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
In Sao Paulo, in addition to a meeting with the governor of the
state, the U.N. chief will visit the headquarters of the Latin
America Parliament, where he will deliver a lecture before
representatives of the civil society on the subject of their
increasingly important role.
</P>
<P>
In Montevideo, Uruguay, the secretary-general will be the guest
of President Julio Maria Sanguinetti with whom he will meet. In
addition to receiving the Keys of the City of Montevideo from its
governor, Annan will address both chambers of the Uruguayan
parliament on the subject of "Contribution to the United Nations
by Small States."
</P>
<P>
In Buenos Aires, Argentina, Annan will also receive the Keys of
the City and, after a meeting with President Carlos Saul Menem, he
will meet with congressional representatives of both the Senate
and the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet with Argentine Civil Society representatives
and deliver a speech before the Argentine Center for International
relations.
</P>
<P>
In Guatemala City, Guatemala, the U.N. chief will hold meetings
with President Alvaro Arzu Irigoyen and the country's government
leadership. Together with the president, the secretary-general
will attend a ceremony marking the presentation of the final
report of the Joint Commission on Education Reform in the presence
of government and indigenous organizations. He will also meet with
representatives of the United Nations Mission in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico City, Mexico, the final stop of his Latin America
trip, the secretary-general will meet with Ernesto Zedillo,
president of Mexico. Following this meeting, Annan, upon accepting
the Keys of the City, will be declared a "distinguished Guest" by
the governor of that city and will be present at a working
luncheon hosted by leaders of the civil society, the business
community and academicians.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general will return to New York during the
weekend of July 25-26, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
