<HEADLINE> Russian Diplomat Arrested for Espionage Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Russian Foreign Ministry
official has been formally taken into custody pending trial on
espionage charges, the Prosecutor General's Office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although the office didn't reveal the identity of the official,
who was detained last Friday while meeting with Cho Sung-woo, a
councilor of the South Korean embassy, but media reports
identified him as Valentin Moiseyey, deputy director of the
Russian Foreign Ministry's First Asian Department.
</P>
<P>
According to the Russian counterintelligence service, Cho is
the South Korean special service's station chief in Moscow, the
Interfax news agency reported. He was declared persona non grata
Saturday and ordered to leave the country in three days.
</P>
<P>
There were Russian Foreign Ministry documents in Cho's
briefcase and the South Korean diplomat declined to say how they
were obtained, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Moiseyev's case is now being investigated by the Federal
Security Service (FSB), the Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
Tass quoted FSB officials as saying that Moiseyev had
systematically provided confidential information to the South
Korean secret service, causing substantial damage to Moscow's
political and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
If convicted of "high treason" as prescribed in the Russian
Criminal Code, Moiseyev could face up to 20 years in prison,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has protested over the expulsion, saying it will
take action after questioning Cho, who is to arrive in Seoul late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Russia and South Korea established diplomatic ties in 1990 and
have since enjoyed good relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
