<HEADLINE> Britain, Orangemen Continue Standoff in Portadown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Protestant Orangemen in
Portadown were preparing for a second night at their makeshift
encampment after being prevented from marching down the Garvaghy
Road.
</P>
<P>
The Orangemen insisted they would not leave Drumcree Church
until they could pass through the Garvaghy Road, a traditional
parade route barred by the Parades Commission last week, according
to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
Although the standoff went on Sunday afternoon, Portadown
itself was calm. Police in black riot gear rested on the bonnets
of slate-grey tank-shaped armored trucks, balaclavas over their
faces.
</P>
<P>
The Orange Order had urged its members to protest peacefully
and Sunday passed without major incident in the largely Protestant
town of Portadown.
</P>
<P>
However, in other parts of Northern Ireland, there was
widespread street violence overnight, with youths throwing petrol
bombs at police, blockading roads and hijacking cars as a protest
against the ban decision made by the Parade Commission.
</P>
<P>
The spreading conflict threatened to torpedo a hard-won accord,
concluded in April, to bring peace to Northern Ireland after 30
years of sectarian and political violence that claimed 3,600
lives. 
</P>
