<HEADLINE> Libyan, Chadian Planes Defy Air Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Libyan and Chadian planes landed
in a Libyan airport Monday in defiance of the United Nations air
embargo, the Libyan News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Chadian plane arrived in the morning at the Al-Abraq
airport, some 1200 kilometers east to the Libyan capital city
Tripoli, while the Libyan aircraft arrived at the same airport in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan plane was dispatched by Libyan leader Moammar
Gadhafi to the Chadian capital N'djamena to fetch Chad's President
Idriss Deby and his Niger's counterpart Ibrahim Mainassara. The
two leaders flew to Libya to attend the grand ceremony marking the
birthday of Islamic Prophet Mohammed to be held late Monday in
Al-Bayda, northeastern Libya.
</P>
<P>
Other members of the Chadian delegation flew to Libya in the
Chadian plane.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Muslim representatives from worldwide are expected
to attend the prayer held in Al-Bayda.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the latest action was in line with the recent
summit of the Organization of African Unity, which called on its
member states to ignore the U.N. sanctions in cases of
humanitarian or religious needs.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed an air and arms embargo on Libya in 1992 to
demand it extradite two Libyan men accused in the bombing of a Pan
Am airliner that killed 270 people on board.
</P>
<P>
Gadhafi has repeatedly defied the embargo by sending planes to
Saudi Arabia carrying pilgrims for the annual Islamic
pilgrimage. He himself flew to Cairo to attend an Arab summit in
1996 and made a tour of West Africa last year.
</P>
<P>
The Chadian plane was the second non-Libyan plane that has
broken the air embargo following an Italian lawmaker's flight to
Tripoli on a humanitarian mission in a small plane last April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
