at the U.N. Headquarters in New York Monday to pay respect to U.N.
Special Envoy in Angola Maitre Alioune Beye and his seven
colleagues from the U.N. mission in the country who lost their
lives in the aircraft crash which occurred on June 26, 1998.
</P>
<P>
After observing one minute of silence, U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan made a statement by saying, "This may give us occasion
to pause and reflect upon what we do. It would be melodramatic to
say that our work is to wage a war for peace; but it is
appropriate to say that we seek to build defenses against
violence, poverty, injustice and destruction."
</P>
<P>
"We must carry on the cause of peace -- in Angola as anywhere
else we can make a difference -- no matter how great the risk, no
matter how absent the immediate reward," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
July 1998 also marked the 50th anniversary of the first
peacekeeping fatalities of the U.N. Organization. Rene de
Labarriere of the United Nations Truce Supervision Organization in
Palestine was killed 50 years ago today. His colleague Ole Bakke
died a week later.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the memorial service were President of the
Security Council Lavrov Sergey and President of the General
Assembly hennadiy Udovenko. 
