<HEADLINE> Tanzania Plans to Build Dry Dock for Rwandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Harbors
Authority (THA) is in the process of setting up a dry dock that
will be used as a transit facility for Rwandan cargoes.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed Monday by William Kusila, the Minister of
Communications and Transport, who accompanied Rwandan President
Pasteur Bizimungu for a tour to the Dar es Salaam Harbor.
</P>
<P>
The decision to put up the facility at Isaka in the northwest
region of Shinyanga followed consultations between the two
countries, Kusila said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the installation of the facility to be
completed by March next year, is aimed at facilitating the
transportation of Rwandan cargoes imported through the Dar es
Salaam port.
</P>
<P>
"I hope within eight months Rwandans will be able to clear
their cargoes at Isaka," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although few cargoes to Rwanda have been routed through
Tanzania over the past few years, Kusila said, the transportation
of the cargoes has not been easy due to floods caused by El Nino
that disrupted Tanzania's communication network including the
central railway line.
</P>
<P>
THA managing director Samson Luhigo said Tanzania will invest
heavily in the installation of the facility.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania has already committed itself to the project," he
said, adding "We also want Rwanda to be earnest."
</P>
<P>
According to Luhigo, the Dar es Salaam port can handle four
million tons of dry cargoes but only half of the capacity is
currently being utilized.
</P>
<P>
In the last five years, he said, Rwanda had about 2.4 million
tons of cargoes through maritime trade. Some 27 percent of the
total, or 640,000 tons, were routed through the Dar es Salaam
port.
</P>
<P>
The managing director said Rwandan goods passing through Dar
es Salaam dropped drastically from 162,953 tons in 1993 to
119,997 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
"The drop in traffic was alarming enough to prompt us to take
a fresh look at what could have gone wrong in terms of port
efficiency, transport modalities and other issues pertaining to
transit trade," Luhigo said.
</P>
<P>
In response to the problem, transport institutions from both
countries met clients and regulatory bodies in the Rwandan
capital of Kigali last year to seek solutions.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu commended the Tanzanian government for its
cooperation and said Rwanda will do its best to speed up cargo
transportation at the port.
</P>
<P>
During his tour, the Rwandan president who was also
accompanied by the Minister of Foreign Affairs and International
Co-operation Jakaya Kikwete, visited the port's general cargo
terminal where 1,600 tons of salt are awaiting transportation to
Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
