<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Russia Agree to Promote Military Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Russia Agreed here Monday
to promote a military dialogue in Cyprus in a bid to realize the
island's ultimate demilitarisation, a Greek Foreign Ministry
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the two U.N. resolutions passed in
June provide a good basis for the assumption of initiatives to
promote a military dialogue and a reduction of the presence of
military forces on the island, aiming at its ultimate
demilitarisation, said the statement released after meetings of
Greece's Alternate Foreign Minister George Papandreou and Foreign
Undersecretary Yiannos Kranidiotis with visiting Russian envoy for
Cyprus Vladimir Tchizhov.
</P>
<P>
The statement continued that Kranidiotis told Tchizhov that the
international community had to make it clear in every way to the
Turkish side that it would tolerate neither the status quo nor the
island's partition, nor any other solution that would be in
violation of the spirit and the letter of the relevant U.N.
decisions and resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Russian envoy stressed the need of strengthening contacts
between the two communities at the level of the society of
citizens because this could contribute to a de-escalation of
tension in the island, which has been divided since 1974 when
Turkish troops occupied the northern third of the island in the
wake of an abortive coup-backed by Athens.
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo problem, the two sides expressed reservations
concerning the prospect of an international military intervention
and generally a further militarisation of the issue, and they also
repeated their positions of seeking a diplomatic solution to the
Kosovo problem, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's meeting with his Yugoslav
counterpart Slobodan Milosevic recently had opened a window to a
diplomatic solution, Tchizhov said, adding that the final status
of Kosovo should be the subject of talks and political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official also considered as particularly positive
the development of an international mechanism for monitoring
Kosovo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
