<HEADLINE> Britain, China Discuss Possible Waste-Water Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- British Deputy Prime Minister John
Prescott told the UK-China Water Sector Cooperation Seminar in
Shanghai that it is time for Britain and China to cooperate in
dealing with water problems.
</P>
<P>
Prescott told the more than 130 experts gathered for the
two-day seminar that there is a unique opportunity for cooperation
between the United Kingdom and China in the water industry, as the
new millennium approaches.
</P>
<P>
British business people spoke about their own experiences in
private-public partnership and about investment and waste water
treatment. By the 1990's, the UK had turned over ten regional
water industry administrations into companies and improved water
supplies.
</P>
<P>
British companies represented at the seminar said they hope to
build long-term relations with China. Bovis Construction Group and
Thames Water International have taken their business to Shanghai,
to work on providing 400,000 cu.m. of water a day.
</P>
<P>
The UK had 5.3 billion U.S. dollars worth of investment in the
field in China by the end of last year, making it No.1 among
European nations.
</P>
<P>
Prescott's China visit with people in the water business is
expected to be good for cooperation in the water industry, which
is listed by the Chinese government as a key area of environmental
protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
