<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan Calls for Equal Division of Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Turkmen President
Saparmurat Niyazov said here Tuesday that the Caspian Sea should
be divided among the five littoral states equally and fairly.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov made the remark in meeting with Iranian Majlis
(Parliament) Speaker Nateq Nouri Tuesday, the official news agency
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov said the differences among the littoral states -
Russia, Iran, Turkmenistan, Kazakstan and Azerbaijan - arise from
the absence of a legal regime for the Caspian resources and lack
of a mechanism for their exploitation.
</P>
<P>
Nouri said that the five states should make their final
decision on a legal regime to stop others from taking advantage of
the current situation.
</P>
<P>
Of the five Caspian states, Turkmenistan, Kazakstan and
Azerbaijan favor a division of the world's largest inland water,
while Iran and Russia hope each of them has equal rights to
exploit Caspian resources.
</P>
<P>
Referring to bilateral relationship, Niyazov said Turkmenistan
considers it important and productive, and called on Iranian
parliament to share with his country the experience in elections.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the West has no accurate understanding of our
religious beliefs, culture and tradition and that's why they raise
the human rights issues."
</P>
<P>
"We believe in our religion and are willing to protect our
cultural identity and this is what the westerners should
understand," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nouri said that Iranian Majlis is ready to share experience
with the Turkmen Parliament on elections and legislation.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized Western countries for adopting double
standard in treating their allies and non-allied states on human
rights issues.
</P>
<P>
Nouri said that reconstruction and development require security
and stability and Iran expects the Caspian states to open up the
avenues for economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Turkmen president arrived here Monday on a three-day visit
to discuss with Iranian leaders the division of Caspian resources
and Caspian oil transport through Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran has close economic ties with Turkmenistan, its northern
neighbor. A gas pipeline inaugurated earlier this year now pumps
3.8 billion cubic meters of natural gas a year from Turkmenistan
to Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
