<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Sees Lower Economic Growth Rate This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The administration of new Philippine
President Joseph Estrada does not expect the economy to grow
beyond 2.5 percent this year as projected by the previous
government, Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During ceremonies marking his takeover from former Finance
Secretary Salvador Enriques, Espiritu admitted that the new
government more realistically expects the growth to be lower than
2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, inflation rate, which was targeted by the
previous government to range between 7.5 percent to 8.5 percent
for the whole of 1998, is now expected to average over 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said that the much lower growth figure and higher
inflation expectation was confirmed following at least two
meetings of the cabinet economic cluster.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said the government is expected to make a downward
revision in key economic targets following the region-wide
economic downturn caused by the continuing currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government of former President Fidel Ramos already lowered
last month the economic growth rate to between 2.5 percent and 3
percent from between 3 percent to 4 percent it set earlier.
</P>
<P>
On the fiscal sector alone, Espiritu acknowledged that there is
a strong possibility that the budget deficit, originally projected
by Enriques to hit 36 billion pesos (900 million U.S. dollars)
this year, could go beyond 40 billion pesos (1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The downscaling of key economic targets has been relayed to the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) which will send a team here in
August to review the country's economic performance, Espiritu
said.
</P>
<P>
Details of the revisions would be discussed between the IMF
team and the Philippine government, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
