<HEADLINE> FIFA President Says World Cup Finals Too Long </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- FIFA president Sepp Blater described
the World Cup finals "too long" and should be shortened.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said to a Swiss newspaper Der Bund:"In the group phase,
teams had six days between matches. That's too many. It shouldn't
be longer than four days."
</P>
<P>
Blatter admitted that it's risky to cram too many matches
together, but said:"The danger also exists if the World Cup lasts
for 33 days."
</P>
<P>
Blatter also denied that he had promised the 2006 World Cup to
Africa, but said that a rotation system among America, Africa, Asia
and Europe is "logical".
</P>
<P>
Blatter said:"Africa needs to be able to offer the necessary
structures if it is to be awarded the tournament." 
</P>
