<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Schools Urged to Teach Local Languages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- It is government policy that the
teaching of indigenous languages within the school system should
be compulsory, Zimbabwean Minister of Education, Sport and
Culture Gabriel Machinga said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Zimbabwe News Agency, the minister
said: "Every child in primary schools should be exposed to at
least one indigenous language and the English language."
</P>
<P>
It is disturbing that some schools do not make it compulsory
for pupils to learn vernacular languages, Machinga said, adding
that "it is always better for the responsible heads to teach the
correct thing without being forced."
</P>
<P>
In most of the country's private schools, Shona and Ndebele
subjects are optional, and only those interested sit for the
examinations at grade seven level.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, he said, has received proposals by groups
advocating for Shona, Ndebele and English to be accorded equal
status.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that it is an advantage to students to be
proficient in all local languages.
</P>
<P>
The issue of developing local languages has been widely
debated in the country.
</P>
<P>
Some groups have said that Africa would remain backward
scientifically, technologically and economically unless schools
started using vernacular languages as the medium of instruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
