<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: 26.6 Million Hectares for Agricultural Reclamation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- China has 26.6 million hectares of
land that could be transformed into agricultural uses if rational
land development and requisition are taken into consideration, the
Beijing-based Economic Daily reported on July 5.
</P>
<P>
The report said that there are three major sources for
reclaiming farmland. Primarily, if China's per capita township and
rural residential land occupation drops to 100 square meters from
the present 153, then 6.3 million hectares would be saved, an
amount more than the total land area allocated for
non-agricultural use in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, about 40 percent of China's urban land calls for a more
efficient use, as the waste is most frequently seen in real estate
and industrial land use, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
According to scientific estimates, 15 percent of developed
urban real estate remains idle, which accounts for 266,666
hectares. As for industrial construction, an average site coverage
is usually 11-to-13 percent higher than that in developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Urban planning and old city renovation can also help improve
the land-use rate and save 180,000-to-360,000 hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, China has 35 million hectares of wasteland that can be
exploited for agricultural use, the paper reported. If only 2
percent of that land is opened up annually, the coverage can make
up for the farmland lost for various purpose during the same
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
