<HEADLINE> Building Permits Value Down in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The total value of building permits
declined in Canada for the second consecutive month in May,
Statistics Canada said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Municipalities in the country issued building permits valued at
2.7 billion dollars (1.8 billion U.S. dollars) in May, down 5.9
percent from April.
</P>
<P>
The residential sector accounted for about three-quarters of
the month's decline, the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the housing sector, municipalities issued 1.4 billion
dollars in building permits in May, down 8.6 percent from
April. The value of permits for both single- and multi-family
dwellings has declined for two consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
In the non-residential sector, construction intentions fell for
a third consecutive month in May, declining 2.8 percent from April
to 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Declines in planned commercial and institutional projects more
than offset the increase in industrial intentions.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the declines, total building permits issued during
the first five months of this year were still 13.2 percent above
the level during the same period last year, the agency added.
</P>
</TEXT>
