<HEADLINE> Indonesia Puts off Plan to Host PATA Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has put off its plan to
host the Pacific Asia Travel Association (PATA) conference in 2000
due to funding difficulties, a minister was quoted by Antara News
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The country is concerned (about the present situation),"
Tourism, Arts and Culture Minister Marzuki Usman told reporters
Tuesday in Denpasar, capital of Bali Province.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has hosted the conference three times in 1963, 1974
and 1991. The minister declined to specify which country will
succeed Indonesia as the host of the PATA conference.
</P>
<P>
PATA with about 2,000 members, including ministers and
businessmen, is regarded as having contributed significantly to
the regional development and marketing of the Asia-Pacific
region's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian tourism sector is most affected by a series of
problems in the country ranging from natural disasters to economic
and political crisis. The government projected the country's
foreign tourist arrivals may fall 5 percent this year from that of
1997.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that only 20 percent of the country's
approximately 4,200 travel bureaus were currently still operating
amidst the protracted economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign tourists, Indonesia's tourism industry will
launch a promotion campaign dubbed "Let's Go Indonesia" this
month.  
</P>
