<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Grain Market Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Beijing released a plan for
increasing grain market reforms today that will push state-owned
grain enterprises into the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
This means that all state-owned grain enterprises, including
grain storage enterprises at the township level in the Chinese
capital will become self-regulating economic entities and will no
longer be subject to government administration.
</P>
<P>
Jia Qinglin, Beijing's mayor, says that all state-owned grain
enterprises should respect the market mechanism and have better
management and performance in a market-oriented economy.
</P>
<P>
According to Liang Wei, head of the Beijing Municipal Grain
Bureau, in addition to the greater commercial independence, there
will be a downsizing of state-owned grain enterprises in Beijing,
from 61,000 employees to about 30,000, and an effort will be made
to restructure these enterprises and to improve the quality of
employees.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to avoid any new deficits by June 1 of next
year," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
