Liu said that China's gold jewelry market is far from being
fully explored, even though every year over 200 tons of gold
jewelry have been sold since 1991. In 1997, China used 340 tons of
gold, making it the world's third largest consumer, after the
United States and India.
</P>
<P>
China's economy has grown at least 8 percent yearly since the
end of the '80s, which Liu believes has greatly helped the gold
jewelry market. The best indication of this, he says, is the more
than 10,000 gold jewelry shops that have appeared.
</P>
<P>
A survey to Chinese cities like Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou
showed that 40 to 50 percent of the residents had bought some gold
jewelry, and the figure in medium-sized and small cities and rural
areas was about 15 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
At present, Liu says, per capita ownership of gold jewelry in
China is less than two grams, far less than the average for other
developing countries, and, "If every Chinese buys just a gram of
gold jewelry, then a thousand tons of gold will be needed, and no
other country has such a huge market."
</P>
<P>
"Every year there are more than 10 million young couples
getting married in China. If one couple buys only 10 grams of gold
jewelry, then a 100-ton gold market will appear," he adds. And,
the Chinese have a tradition of seeing gold jewelry as a sign of
wealth, and this helps provide a large gold jewelry market in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
