<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Tanzania Pledge Stronger Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Rwanda and
Tanzania announced Tuesday that the two countries will intensify
bilateral cooperation and work together to solve regional
problems through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made in a joint communique issued here
before Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu winded up his
three-day state visit to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, President Bizimungu and his
Tanzanian counterpart Benjamin Mkapa agreed to explore new ways
for further strengthening and consolidating of the existing
cordial neighborly relations.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents emphasized the greater need for the
consolidation of peace, security and stability along their common
border to create a conducive environment for trade and other
forms of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to regularly hold good-neighborly meetings, and
called for revitalization of cooperation arrangements in various
sectors between their two countries in the framework of the Joint
Permanent Commission.
</P>
<P>
During the talks between the two presidents, Bizimungu
underlined the importance of the private sector in fostering
development in Africa, while Mkapa stressed the need to promote
trade between countries in the continent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two sides have decided to construct a dry
dock at Isaka station on Tanzania's central railway to speed up
the movement of Rwanda cargoes.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also reaffirmed the need to build a railway
linking Isaka, Shinyanga region in the northwest of Tanzania,
with the Rwandan capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The line could be extended to the eastern areas of the
Democratic Republic of Congo, as well as Uganda. They have
directed the relevant authorities of their countries to implement
the cross-border project.
</P>
<P>
On regional issues, the two presidents underscored the
importance of regional cooperation and economic integration so as
to resolve some regional problems.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda was commended for its desire to join the East African
Cooperation (EAC) as a move in the right direction. EAC is a
regional bloc comprising Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On the border conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea, Bizimungu
and Mkapa called on the two countries at war to resolve the
crisis by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
In this connection, they voiced support to the OAU mediation
efforts led by its current chairman, President Blaise Campaore of
Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents held extensive discussions on the situation
prevailing in the Great Lakes region, particularly the crisis in
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents welcomed the progress made in the first
session of the Burundi peace talks during June 15-21 in the
northern Tanzanian town of Arusha and the commitment made by all
parties represented in the peace talks to engage in serious
negotiations with the aim of resolving the conflict in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
They further welcomed the unanimous agreement by the Burundi
parties to put an end to hostilities. In this regard, they called
on all the belligerents to honor the commitment to suspend
hostilities immediately.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu left Tanzania Tuesday. Before flying home, the
Rwandan President held a press conference in the State House
here.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan President arrived here Sunday with his wife
Seraphina Bizimungu and a delegation of cabinet ministers and
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Bizimungu officially opened the 22nd Dar es
Salaam International Trade Fair, visited the Dar es Salaam port
and Tanzania-China Friendship Textiles Co. Ltd, and held talks
with members of the Tanzanian Business Community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
