<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Annual College Examination Begins (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The annual entrance examination
which will select elite students for China's colleges and
universities makes the whole nation the world's biggest
examination hall today.
</P>
<P>
About 3.2 million high school graduates were expected to attend
the national examination that began all over the country at 9:00
am this morning. There are 340,000 more students taking the exam
this year than last year, according to a spokesman of the Ministry
of Education.
</P>
<P>
One member of the giant army of examinees, Li Ran got to his
examination place one hour prior to the starting time.
</P>
<P>
"For the exam, I even quit watching the live presentations of
the World Cup," the student from the Beijing Erlonglu Middle School
said, looking a bit nervous.
</P>
<P>
Li has reason to give up his favorite soccer matches, since the
examination is considered a turning point in the destiny of many
Chinese: a college education often means job opportunities, a
successful career and the attainment of wealth.
</P>
<P>
"We've prepared for this exam for a decade," says a middle-aged
women whose daughter is taking the exam. "This (to help her
succeed) is the top priority of our family."
</P>
<P>
The woman waiting outside her daughter's examination room
refuses to be identified because she does not want her daughter
to know. "It may make her more nervous," she explains.
</P>
<P>
China has held this examination for 21 years since its
reinstitution after it was forced to halt during the chaotic
Cultural Revolution (1966-76).
</P>
<P>
The decision to resume the exam, announced by the late Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping, is regarded as a powerful engine that helped
to boost the country's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
With a tradition of respect for education, China initiated an
examination system to help ordinary people win official positions
more than 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Today, times have changed. As Chinese leaders urge the
revitalization of the nation through science and technology, study
at colleges and universities has become a symbol of success.
</P>
<P>
Some examinees and their parents have brought with them cold
drinks, food and even bags of oxygen, as they converge in front of
the gate of the Affiliated School of the Beijing Normal University
where the examination is being held.
</P>
<P>
"Preparatory work is OK, and even a medical team is ready,"
says a teacher named Ma. He explains that several students usually
faint from anxiety and nervousness every year.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry asks local departments to keep an eye out for
cheats during the exam. In some flooded areas, motor boats have
been deployed to transport examinees," says Wang Xuming, an
official with the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
Psychologists appear on TV talk shows to comfort anxious
students and their parents. The State General Administration for
Environmental Protection has issued a circular forbidding noisy
construction prior to and during the exam, as it may adversely
affect examinees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Annual College Examination Begins (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some 1,000 Chinese universities and colleges will enroll an
additional 70,000 students this year, which means that one out of
every three examinees will be able to find a place on campus. In
spite of this, most people agree that they are under greater
pressure than ever before.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by psychologists at East China Normal
University and Shanghai University shows that the degree of nerves
and anxiety suffered by the students' parents has increased
dramatically this year.
</P>
<P>
Ma Wansheng, a father accompanying his daughter to the exam,
says that Chinese parents are feeling greater responsibility since
their daughter or son is usually an only child as a result of the
birth control policy adopted in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shouyu, headmaster of Beijing's No.15 Middle School, says
that the reform of state-enterprises and the restructuring of
government departments have made the employment situation
difficult, and that many companies require that their employees be
college graduates.
</P>
<P>
"This is an outcome of the fast growth of the Chinese economy,"
Wang adds.
</P>
<P>
Specialities the examinees most wish to study include finance,
accounting, foreign languages and computer science, subjects
closely related to the current reality in China.
</P>
<P>
It has been one year since China entirely abolished the
40-year-odd system of free tuition for college students. However,
some universities have shown a willingness to provide subsidies
for students from poverty-stricken rural areas if they pass the
examination this year.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has again urged that the system of
higher education, which originated from the rigid Soviet model, be
further reformed, and a plan to reform the current college
examination structure is now under discussion.
</P>
<P>
The media have suggested that students should not be the slaves
of examination grades, but must improve their overall capabilities.
</P>
<P>
This year's college entrance examination will be attended by
more boys than girls by a ratio of two to one, and 63 percent of
the examinees have expressed a wish to study natural science or
engineering.
</P>
<P>
Chinese language and politics are today's exam subjects, and
the remainder, including history, English, mathematics, physics
and chemistry, will be completed in the next two days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
