<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- The White House said that U.S. President Bill Clinton would
travel to Russia in early September to meet with Russian President
Boris N. Yeltsin, even though the Russian legislature had not
fulfilled a request to ratify the Start-2 arms control treaty.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton will punish health insurance companies
that deny coverage to sick people, in violation of a 1996 law, by
excluding them from the lucrative insurance market for Federal
employees, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Fresh from his well-received nine-day journey through China,
President Clinton plunged back into the domestic political arena
Monday, challenging a recalcitrant Congress to advance his stalled
legislative agenda in areas such as health care, education and
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
-- Mexico's ruling party suffered a sharp blow in election
results reported Monday, losing the governor's race in the rural,
northern state of Zacatecas, long considered one of the party's
most impervious strongholds. But it staged a startling comeback in
another important northern state, Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Economists predict the brunt of Asia's economic crisis will
hit the U.S. in the next six to nine months, according to a Wall
Street Journal survey. Most of the survey's participants believe
U.S. companies will slow production and cut employment, though the
economy is unlikely to contract. 
</P>
