<HEADLINE> FIFA to Help Players Combat Heat in Next World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- FIFA will study how to help players to
combat heat and humidity in the next World Cup finals to be held in
South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Asked on Tuesday whether the FIFA Medical Committe would study the
effect of morning matches on players' performance, Chairman Michel
D'Hooghe said: "It's not a matter of hours. It's also a matter of heat
and dehydration."
</P>
<P>
At the 2002 World Cups, some games would kick off at 10 in the
morning to cater for the audiences in Europe and South America and may
continue until the noon when the summer heat will be intense.
</P>
<P>
But he said he could do nothing to change the kick-off times even
after he saw the Netherlands and Belgium battled in noon heat as high
as 50 degrees Centigrade at the last World Cup finals in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
"The rights of television (live broadcasting) is stronger than our
medical arguments. I deplore that," he said. "From medical points of
view, it is not sensible to play a game at certain periods of time in
a day and under certain extreme temperatures." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
