<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA May Simplify Doping Procedures in Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Cao Li
</P>
<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The international soccer's governing body
FIFA said it may simplify the doping procedures in the future World
Cups following several years of very low rate of doping cases.
</P>
<P>
"We'll have less and less problems," FIFA Doping Committee Chairman
Lars Peterson told Xinhua on Tuesday. "The risk will be reduced. Maybe
in the future we can simplify the procedures involved if not do away
with the doping tests."
</P>
<P>
FIFA said on Tuesday all the 240 samples taken from players in 60
World Cup games so far were negative. There are only four matches left
in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Two players from each side in a game are tested, with the results
being reported in 24 hours by an IOC-accreditated laboratory in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The main reasons that FIFA maintains a doping control program in
major competitions like the World Cup are to support the general
anti-doping campaign in sports and to show to the youths that soccer
is a clean sport.
</P>
<P>
"A big federation like FIFA could not back away from this," added
the Swede. "They need our support. By doing this, we can show we can
play football at the high level without doping.
</P>
<P>
"It's very important for the young players. They know these players
are clean."
</P>
<P>
FIFA's Medical Committee Chairman Michel D'Hooghe told a news
conference that in Europe the sport has only 1.26 positive cases in
every 1,000 samples, according to a report published two or three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said this was the result of year's anti-doping education and
better collective medical control in the team sport.
</P>
<P>
Some other sports had as high as 7 percent of positive cases,
D'Hooghe said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
