<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The number of farms in Kuwait in 1996-97 fiscal
year (from July 1 to June 30) stood at 3,067, representing a 7
percent rise over the previous year, Tuesday's English daily Arab
Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted official statistics released by the Central
Statistics Department of Kuwaiti Ministry of Planning as saying
that about 56 percent of the farms are engaged in breeding sheep.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural farms accounted for 39 percent of the total and
the remaining 5 percent were poultry and other livestock farms.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996-97 fiscal year, there were about 13,048 workers
in the sector, about 12 percent more than 1995-96. Some 90 percent
of the workers were from Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The total area of the farms during 1996-97 was estimated at
68.5 million square meters, a 9 percent increase over 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
There were 21,023 cows and 534,107 sheep in these farms,
representing 8 percent rises compared with 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Dubai Civil Aviation Department has concluded
an open sky agreement with the Ethiopian Civil Department, the
first of its kind by Ethiopia with another party in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to Tuesday's "Itihad" newspaper of the United Arab
Emirates (UAE), the agreement was signed in Dubai, UAE. It is an
open agreement with regard to the number of flights, departure
terminals, intermediate points and capacity.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Airlines has 12 regular flights to Dubai a week.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The European Union decided to extend a
1.176-million-U.S. dollar grant to the Egyptian Industries
Federation to contribute to organizing the conference of the
European-Mediterranean partnership due to be held in Cairo in
October.
</P>
<P>
The conference is the second biggest gathering since November
1996. About 3,500 companies representing 65 countries will attend
the conference.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Iraqi industrial delegation is due in Cairo this
month on a week-long visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which includes heads of cotton, textiles,
weaving and wool departments, will conclude agreements with Egypt
on renovating Iraqi factories, providing necessary spare parts and
dispatching groups of experts in the fields of weaving and
textiles to re-operate Iraqi plants.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed that Egypt will export to Iraq 1,000
tonnes of yarn, 5 million meters of woolen and cotton fabrics,
100,000 bed sheets and 100,000 tents worth 25 million dollars.


07/07/98 13:6 GMT

NNNN
21:14 21:14 g # PAB
</P>
