<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Razes Quarter of Kenya's Game Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Three fires started by nomadic
herdsmen, charcoal burners and tourists have destroyed about a
quarter of Tsavo East National Park in southeastern Kenya, the
Kenya Wildlife Service (KWS) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the last fire was put down Monday night and now about
40 rangers are keeping a 24-hour watch to ensure no new fire
fronts opened up, KWS spokesman John Mramba told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The fire, first starting three weeks ago, destroyed nearly 365
square kilometers of Tsavo East's 1,100 square kilometers. Tsavo
East, together with the larger Tsavo West, comprise the biggest
wildlife park in this east African nation.
</P>
<P>
Together, they have 20,000 square kilometers and are located
about 290 kilometers southeast of the Kenyan capital of Nairobi.
Most of the endangered species such as rhino and hirolla antelope
have their sanctuaries in Tsavo East.
</P>
<P>
However, the area under fire is not densely populated by wild
animals and all large animals have moved out of the area, Mramba
quoted sources in Tsavo as saying.
</P>
<P>
No reports on casualties are available.
</P>
<P>
Mramba said the first two fires extinguished over the weekends
were caused by charcoal burners and pastoralists burning bushes
to kill ticks.
</P>
<P>
The third fire had been detected at Kanderi area Sunday night
and was spreading fast as it was being fanned by strong winds. It
was believed to have been started by a lit cigarette dropped on
the dry grass by a tourist.
</P>
<P>
It was finally put down Monday night as the KWS "mobilized
everything on the ground" to curtain fire and create firebreaks,
according to the officials with KWS.
</P>
<P>
"It is a big fire with large fronts due to changes of wind
directions," said John Muhanga, KWS assistant director at Tsavo
East park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
