<HEADLINE> Israeli Hawkish Minister Proposes Withdrawal Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon said on Tuesday that he has proposed to the Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee of the Knesset (Parliament) a new
plan on Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
After addressing the committee, Sharon told reporters that he
has suggested Israel hand over to the Palestinians less than the
proposed areas of the West Bank, but give them other incentives.
</P>
<P>
But he did not go further with his plan, saying that it has not
been discussed in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"If the current efforts to move the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks do not succeed, another direction must be tried," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has reportedly proposed that Israel pull back
from 13.1 percent of the West Bank in exchange for Palestinian
commitments to fighting against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted the proposal, but Israel has
not. The Jewish state, citing security interests of the country,
insists that it will withdraw from no more than 9 percent of the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Sharon, a key and hawkish member of the Israeli cabinet, argues
that even withdrawal from 9 percent of the West Bank will endanger
Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
He has drawn up his own security map for the West Bank,
demanding to set up a 10 to 20-kilometer long security zone in
west of the West Bank and another seven to 10-kilometer long
security strip along the Jordan Valley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
