<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Compete for Profitable Housing Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Competition seems to be mounting
among Chinese banks as they all try to gain a foothold in the
housing financing market at a time when the housing sector is
becoming one of the new growth areas in the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
One of the four largest Chinese commercial banks, the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC), plans to include
housing financing in its package of major services in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
Housing loans, which now account for only three percent of the
bank's total loans, is expected to increase to ten percent by the
end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The bank also plans to issue 30 billion yuan in housing loans
this year, about 15 percent of all loans expected to be extended
this year.
</P>
<P>
The ICBC has seen rapid expansion in its housing financing
since it first launched such services. Statistics show that
between 1991 and last May, the bank's housing deposits tripled,
reaching 72.7 billion yuan, with housing loans increasing by 250
percent to 60.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months of this year, the bank issued 12.2
billion yuan in housing loans, including 2.43 billion yuan for
residential house-buyers.
</P>
<P>
ICBC officials said that the bank will focus its housing
financing on large and medium-sized cities with good market
potential for housing sales, and give priority to large and
medium-sized real estate developers and building companies.
</P>
<P>
"Residential housing, government-subsidized housing for the
poor and renovation projects will be considered first in loan
applications, and commercial highrises, villas, and luxury
apartments will definitely receive no bank loans, " said an ICBC
official.
</P>
<P>
The bank also promised support for the secondary housing
market, since house trading is expected to be essential to
ongoing housing reform. The bank is now considering providing
loans and such services as settlements, consulting and asset
evaluation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
