<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poorest Ethnic Group Shaking off Poverty (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Bajiu Ergu, 71, was somewhat
puzzled when he moved into his new home with an independent toilet
built at a cost of more than 30,000 yuan (about 3,600 U.S.
dollars). The elderly member of the Yi Nationality dared not
believe that it was his own house.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, he lived in a mud-brick house together with his
sheep, pigs and other domestic animals.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the local government, his family earned more
than 50,000 yuan (about 6,000 U.S. dollars) last year from raising
livestock, and the per capita grain outpout for the family was
more than 700 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The improved living standard for the family has been the result
of a project launched by the Chinese government to help Yi people
change their habits, and improve living conditions and the local
environment with a goal of eradicating poverty in the region.
</P>
<P>
The project has brought benefits to a lot of Yi people in the
Liangshan Yi Autonomous Prefecture, southwest China's Sichuan
Province in addition to Bajiu Ergu.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, at present, the per capita income for Yi
people in the prefecture has exceeded 980 yuan (about 110
U.S. dollars) and per capita grain production has surpassed 410
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
One million formerly impoverished people now are well-fed and
more than 150,000 families have moved into new houses.
</P>
<P>
The Yi Nationality is the sixth largest ethnic group in China,
with a population of more than 6.5 million. This ethnic group
scatters mainly over mountainous regions in the provinces of
Sichuan, Yunnan, Guizhou and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
