<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan FM Calls for Regional Peace, Harmony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Foreign Minister
Lakshman Kadiragamar on Tuesday stressed the need to promote peace
and harmony in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Kadiragamar was talking to the media at Islamabad Airport
before his departure for Colombo after a three-day visit to
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He arrived here Sunday as a special envoy of Sri Lankan
President Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga to deliver an
invitation letter to Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif for
attending the 10th summit of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) scheduled to be held from July 29 to
31 in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need to lessen tension in South Asia, the Sri
Lankan foreign minister said the SAARC can promote peace and
harmony in the region.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that at the forthcoming SAARC summit a
good attempt would be made in this direction.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the possible role of the SAARC in the wake of
the nuclearization of India and Pakistan, Kadiragamar said, "We
are looking into the question as to what other SAARC countries can
do to de-escalate tension in the region."
</P>
<P>
"Sri Lanka on its part would try to make a positive
contribution for this purpose as it was convinced that without
peace and security the region would only be limping along," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan, who bade farewell
to Kadiragamar at the airport, said Sharif and his Indian
counterpart, Atal Bihari Vajpayee, is expected to have a bilateral
meeting in Colombo during the summit and Pakistan will again call
upon India to agree on a just solution to the core issue of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"It is our earnest hope that India would rise to the occasion,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Gohar noted that Pakistan has been welcoming offers by the U.N.
secretary general and various countries of assistance and good
offices for the resolution of the core issue. But unfortunately
India rejected all these gestures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation arising from the nuclearization of
India and Pakistan, Gohar pointed out that now there is a greater
need to work for the solution of the Kashmir issue and for peace
and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
The 10th SAARC summit will be attended by leaders of its member
countries including Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
