<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poorest Ethnic Group Shaking off Poverty (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Located in the southwest part of Sichuan Province, Liangshan Yi
Autonomous Prefecture, with a Yi population of 1.6 million, is the
largest region in China inhabited by Yi people.
</P>
<P>
Bajiu Ergu said that for a long period and just like their
predecessors, Yi people ate corn and buckwheat as their staple
food and many of them were forced to eat tree roots and wild
vegetables for half a year because of a grain shortage.
</P>
<P>
The slave-owning system was abolished in the prefecture in
1952, when the Chinese government adopted a reform through
consultations and established the autonomous prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1993 show that 2.1 million out of the
prefecture's 3.82 million people lived with a per capita annual
income of less than 500 yuan (about 60 U.S. dollars), with the per
capita grain production less than 400 kilograms annually.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has made poverty relief in the
prefecture a high priority. From 1994 to now, the central
government and governments at all levels in Sichuan Province have
allocated 33 million yuan (about 3.97 million U.S. dollars) to help
more people shake off poverty in the prefecture.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the central government allocated 10 million yuan
(about 1.2 million U.S. dollars) for the prefecture to start a
housing project.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts are beginning to pay off, according to
provincial officials. Many of the Yi people have moved into new
houses, use energy-saving stoves for cooking and have running
water. Many of them have also equipped their houses with modern
furniture and electric appliances.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
