<HEADLINE> Financial Distress Dampens Economic Recovery in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Bad economic news in the second quarter
of 1998 has cast a shadow on the relatively promising outlook for the
Russian economy at the beginning of the year, according to a United
Nations survey published here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The weak signs of recovery began to fade with the publication of
zero growth figure for the first quarter," said the UN Economic
Commission for Europe (UN/ECE) in its Economic Survey of Europe. "The
April figures did not show any improvement and confirmed that GDP had
remained flat in the first four months of the year."
</P>
<P>
"Financial turmoil culminated in the last week of May when the
Central Bank of the Russian Federation raised its refinancing rate to
the crisis level of 150 percent as a last resort to defend the
currency," said the survey.
</P>
<P>
"The deterioration of the economic situation in 1998 is at least
partly due to the sharp fall of commodity prices which has led to a
substantial fall in export revenues,"said the survey.
</P>
<P>
"The negative impact of this fall is not confined to the corporate
sector but also affects Russia's external balances and the public
finances," it said.
</P>
<P>
The UN/ECE admitted that the outlook for the Russian economy was
not at all clear when the report was written. "Russian financial
markets continue to be characterized by a high degree of volatility,
and considerable uncertainties about the future remain," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Although this latest crisis was confined to the financial markets,
it does reflect a number of persistent and fundamental problems in the
Russian economy and these seem to have been the main cause of the
turmoil despite an apparent contagion effect from the Asian crisis,"
it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the UN/ECE expressed hope that Russia would move
ahead with a coherent and comprehensive program of institutional reform
in which the reorganization of the fiscal system should be the top
priority in order to realize financial, and thus macro-economics and
political, stabilization in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sees Continued Fall of Inflation Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The inflation rate in Nigeria
dropped to 6.2 percent in May, three percentage points less than
that of April, according to the Federal Office of Statistics
(FOS).
</P>
<P>
FOS, the federal agency responsible for compilation,
processing and dissemination of statistical information, also
projected that all things being equal, the inflation rate for
June would be six percent.
</P>
<P>
The continued fall of inflation rate, to economic watchers
here, seems to confirm that the government may have succeeded in
its determination to curtail the general price level.
</P>
<P>
The government said in the 1998 budget that it planned to
bring down the inflation level to nine percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Through the regime of tight fiscal policy measures, the
Nigerian government has been able to bring inflation under
control.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact, economists and economic watchers generally
insist that the figure should not be taken as a good measure of
the health of the economy.
</P>
<P>
"Government has done well by substantially bringing down the
inflation level, but it needs to be said that the purchasing
power of consumers is still very low while manufacturing
warehouses are still full of unsold goods," the newspaper This
Day reported Tuesday, quoting an unnamed analyst.
</P>
<P>
To many analysts, with crippling fuel crisis pervading the
greater part of the year and the current political crisis which
have slowed down economic activities, the government may have
difficulties in achieving its projected growth target for this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government, in its 1998 budget, targets a growth
rate of 5.5 percent for this year, compared with 3.77 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, FOS officials also expressed fears that with the
slow start of rainfall this year, agricultural production has
been affected and this may contribute to a slowdown of the
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
