<HEADLINE> SA Minister Expected in Zambia on Kaunda's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense Minister Joe
Modise is expected in Zambia Tuesday to discuss with the Zambian
government on the expected retirement from party politics of
former President Kenneth Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's eldest son, Panji Kaunda, said here Monday that he
was not aware of Modise's coming, Times of Zambia reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he was still holding negotiations with the
government on his father's retirement package.
</P>
<P>
"We as the family are still negotiating for the old man's
retirement package and so far everything is going on very well,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that kaunda's family has proposed that the government
offer state lodge as Kaunda's residence.
</P>
<P>
The family has sidelined the United National Independence
Party (UNIP) led by Kaunda from the negotiations because it does
not want to confuse the issue with partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
Panji Kaunda said "UNIP is in opposition and we do not want to
use it to fight for the old man's retirement package...this is a
family issue and we will do it ourselves."
</P>
<P>
He said his father's name will be kept away from the political
limelight for the next four or more years so that peace could
return to the family.
</P>
<P>
He said he has requested that all of his father's aides stop
from operating at Kalundu House to create a homely atmosphere at
the house, where Kaunda's family is staying.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the government will move quickly to find an
office for the former president so all other political,
professional and career activities could be done away from home.
</P>
<P>
Four days after his release from under house arrest last month
Kaunda announced that he will quit party politics so that he can
serve the nation and the continent on a wider scope.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said that he will step down from politics at the next
extra-ordinary national congress of UNIP.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda had been the country's president since its independence
in 1964 until 1991, when he was defeated by current President
Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 74, was detained on December 25 last year for alleged
involvement in last October 28 coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
Six days after his arrest he was put under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
In February this year he was formally charged with misprision
of treason.
</P>
<P>
After Kaunda's release South African President Nelson Mandela
who mediated the release expressed his hope that Chiluba will not
stop there so that he can make it possible for other leaders to
persuade Kaunda not to continue in party politics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
