<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Import of Overseas Agro-Technology Pays Off in Heilongjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Heilongjiang, a leading grain
producer in northeast China, has succeeded in raising the ratio of
science and technology in agricultural development to 30 percent
by introducing advanced agronomy practices from abroad, sources
with the Provincial Foreign Experts Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Because of rough cultivation and the use of poor seed strains,
the grain output of Heilongjiang had lingered around 10 billion
kilograms for many years, they said.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in the early 1980s, the provincial government each
year invited 200 foreign agricultural experts to give lectures or
pass on up-to-date agro-technology to their Chinese partners and
sent the same amount of Chinese agro-technicians to study abroad,
said Zhang Yichang, director of the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The province invited two Japanese rice specialists to guide
rice cultivation with sparse-planting technology on dry land,
which increased the per unit output by 10-to-20 percent compared
with ordinary cultivation methods.
</P>
<P>
It has also imported high-yield wheat strains and virus-free
and tobacco flue-cured technologies from Canada, sugar beet
breeding technology from Japan and seed-coating technology from
Russia.
</P>
<P>
As a result, its annual grain output soared to 30 billion
kilograms. The economic results it gained from importing overseas
agronomy techniques in the past decade has surpassed 10 billion
yuan, Zhang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Urged to Continue Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's National Assembly
members-elect have commended the new leadership's wide
consultations on the country's political future but kicked
against any attempt to abort the current transition program due
to end on October 1.
</P>
<P>
The members made clear their positions on key national issues
in a statement adopted at a meeting held last Saturday in Abuja
and carried on major national newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The members commended the commitment of the new leader General
Abudulsalam Abubakar to continue the transition program as he
said in his maiden national broadcasting on June 9.
</P>
<P>
They hailed the magnanimity of the government in releasing
some political detainees and called for the release of all
political detainees, including Moshood Abiola, the presumed
winner of the annulled June 12, 1993 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The members, however, claimed that the current consultation by
the Abubakar government is incomplete as it ignored members of
the Local Government, Members-elect of the State and National
Assembly totalling about 11,500.
</P>
<P>
The said members were elected during previous elections held
under the transition program started by late military leader Sani
Abacha and inherited by Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The members stressed that the elections have been adjudged to
be free and fair by the government as well as reputable
international observers.
</P>
<P>
They warned that the cancellation of any election as a
solution to any political crisis will always result in the
consequence of exacerbating the crisis, as proven in the example
of the June 12 election, which is "undoubtedly the major cause of
the current political impasse in Nigeria".
</P>
<P>
The members cautioned that it will be a mockery of Nigeria
before the international community if the government aborts the
current transition program as a product of the consultation
exercise.
</P>
<P>
The members maintain that all political structures and
transition agencies already existing should be retained and that
all Nigerians, including those who felt left out should be
encouraged to join the existing parties.
</P>
<P>
"We identify with and accept the resolve of this Government to
terminate on 1st October, 1998 and hand over to a democratically
elected government," the members said.
</P>
<P>
"For the avoidance of doubt, we the elected members of the
National Assembly, from all the five political parties fervently
stand by out mandate as it is representative of the true wishes
of all Nigerians," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
