<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheap Power May Become History in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa looks set to
lose its status as having one of the cheapest electricity prices
in the world, Business Day paper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 16 countries showed that South Africa's
electricity prices for business and industrial consumers rose by
5.61 percent in the year ended April 1998. This was the third
year running that South Africa registered the steepest rise among
the countries surveyed.
</P>
<P>
The annual National Utility Services survey showed that 10 of
the 16 countries saw a drop in prices, such as the United States,
Britain and Germany. Swedish consumers benefit most with a fall
of 9.79 percent in the country's power prices.
</P>
<P>
South Africa provides its consumers with electricity at 17.49
cents (three U.S. cents) per kilowatt hour.
</P>
<P>
But experts said this is unlikely to last much longer as the
state power utility, Eskom, is heading for commercialization.
</P>
<P>
Sales and marketing manager for the survey, Tommy Taylor, said
the Eskom Amendment Bill recently approved by the National
Assembly would be a catalyst for price hikes.
</P>
<P>
The bill means Eskom will become a limited liability company
paying taxes and dividends - from which it is currently exempt.
</P>
<P>
Eskom may have to increase prices to help fund its commitment
to provide power to 75 percent of the population by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The electricity utility may also have to increase its capital
expenditure in the coming years should its overcapacity dwindle
in the face of the ongoing expansion of its grid to meet its
electrification commitments.
</P>
<P>
An Eskom managing director said earlier that the utility's
revenue growth was projected at 1.8 percent in the year to
December, down from the 9.4 percent rise last year. He said the
volatility in commodity markets is threatening Eskom's sales.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said government was still talking with municipalities,
the national electricity regulator, large users and Eskom on the
restructuring of the electricity industry.
</P>
<P>
"But everything points to much more expensive power," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
