<HEADLINE> Tourists Bring $4.27m to Zanzibar in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 7 (Xinhua) - A total of 86,495 tourists
visited Zanzibar in 1997, bringing 4.27 million U.S. Dollars
revenue to the government, the Minister for Information, Culture,
Tourism and Youth Development has said.
</P>
<P>
Issa Mohammed Issa told Monday the Zanzibar House of
Representatives, which is in session for debating the 1998/99
budget, that the number of visitors has increased from 69,159 and
the income from 1.66 million U.S. Dollars in 1996, Tanzanian
media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He asked the House to endorse a total of 1,420,959,000
Shillings (about 2.153 million U.S. Dollars) for both recurrent
and development expenditure for the 1998/99 fiscal year which is
being on July 1.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the rise in the numbers to concerted efforts to
market the isles abroad by the Tourists Commission, pledging to
make more efforts to consolidate the tourism infrastructure by
upgrading roads, controlling beach erosion and improving
management.
</P>
<P>
Issa also said that the privatization of state-run hotels will
be sped up to improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"The (Tanzanian) Union and Zanzibar governments have agreed in
principle to privatize the ailing Furaha ya Visiwani Hotels
Limited to bail the company out of its present financial
quagmire," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lying in the west of the Indian Ocean and 40 kilometers off
the mid-Tanzanian coast, Zanzibar consists of Unguja, its sister
island Pemba and dozens of small isles. It is famous for the
Arab-style Stone Town, the widely planted cloves and beautiful
beaches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
