<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Development Bank Reports Marked Growth in Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Bank (SDB), a
policy-oriented bank designed to finance the infrastructure and
primary industries in China, issued 53 billion yuan (about 6.4
billion U.S. dollars) in loans during the first six months of this
year, up 19 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The notable growth actually reponds to a national call for
increasing bank loans to infrastructure to ensure an annual
economic growth of eight percent, according to the SDB spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The bank has adopted a series of special measures this year to
secure sufficient and timely loans for infrastructure projects,
including revising its loan-extension plans and signing
preliminary loan agreements with some loan recipients having good
repayment records and financial strength.
</P>
<P>
The bank has increased its loan credit line for the first six
months this year to 53.9 billion yuan, a rise of 24 percent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank originally planned to extend 100 billion yuan in loans
in 1998, but later revised it to 120 billion yuan in response to
the government's demand for an increase in bank loans to offset
the impact of the Asian financial crisis on the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
Some profitable projects also enjoyed a simplified
loan-application process and received early loans by signing
preliminary contracts with the SDB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
