<HEADLINE> Singaporeans Urged To Be More Aware of Disastrous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong has called upon the nation to be more aware of its uniqueness
and the disastrous affects of the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ceremony of launching the National Education
Exhibition Tuesday, the Prime Minister said the exhibition seeks
to make Singaporeans more aware of the uniqueness of the country
and highlights a must to learn the nation's history that many
young Singaporeans are unaware.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the current situation, he said that Singapore has
been relatively unaffected by the Asian currency crisis which he
described like "a bolt from the blue."
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the crisis "dramatically transformed a stable
and rapidly growing region to one fraught with grave uncertainty
and instability."
</P>
<P>
He said that as "Asia is facing a meltdown, How can Singapore
preserve itself, and escape disaster?"
</P>
<P>
The crisis is a timely reminder that challenges can arise
unexpectedly, he said.
</P>
<P>
On display at the nearly month-long exhibition are historical
documents, publications, pictures and material objects to show the
island-state's modern history from the time of the colonial rule
to the present.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 participants including a number of government
ministers attended the inaugural ceremony of the exhibition, the
first large-scale show of its kind in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
