<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Yield Expected to Rise in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Burundi's coffee production is
expected to rise to 25,000 tons in 1998/99 (August/July) from
20,000 tons in the previous year, according to a report issued
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Improved husbandry and a rising availability of fertilizer and
pesticides were helping to boost production, Barthelemy Niyikiza,
the chief of the Burundi Coffee Office (OCIBU), was quoted by a
report from the Kenya Times newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Many farmers who were formerly displaced by insecurity in the
tiny central African nation were able to return to their fields
last year and resume tending previously abandoned coffee trees,
said Niyikiza.
</P>
<P>
"The quality and quantity of the 1998/99 crop will be higher
than last year because there has been better maintenance and we
have been able to distribute fertilizer and treat trees with
pesticides," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In previous years, many farmers were displaced and could not
work their fields, so the coffee was not maintained and the trees
were abandoned," he said, "Now the peasants have started to
return to their fields."
</P>
<P>
Officials at OCIBU, the state-run organization responsible for
selling Burundi's crop of mostly Arabica coffee, said the 1998/99
crop was being harvested and sales would probably start in
August.
</P>
<P>
Coffee production in the country reached a peak of 41,000 tons
in 1994/95, but has steadily declined since then because of a
civil war that has claimed an estimated 150,000 lives since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Output levels were further sapped when neighboring countries
imposed a trade embargo on the land-locked nation in mid-1996 to
punish a military coup.
</P>
<P>
The embargo cut off access to pesticides and fertilizer, but
OCIBU officials say those supplies are arriving again.
</P>
<P>
Niyikiza said OCIBU would start treating trees with pesticides
and begin distributing fertilizer this month in the hope of
boosting production for the 1999/2000 crop, forecast at 30,000
tons.
</P>
<P>
Coffee brings in more than 80 percent of Burundi's foreign
exchange revenues. The majority of Burundi's coffee is grown in
the north and west of the country, with most exports going to
Europe and the Untied States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
