<HEADLINE> Singapore Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Share prices lost ground on the
Singapore stock market Tuesday as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) dropped 12.32 points to 1115.18.
</P>
<P>
Turnover totaled 87.92 million shares, valued at 168.04 million
Singapore dollars (about 98.32 million U.S. dollars). There were
189 losers against 78 gainers while 322 stocks remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MBF Cap was the most active stock which closed on a turnover of
10.47 million units. DBS Land had 6.35 million counters done.
TchongInthk was next with 6.26 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
SIA F topped the gainers of the day as it rose by 25 cents to
8.5 Singapore dollars. Jurship gained 15 cents to finish at 8.3
Singapore dollars while Boustd rose by 13 cents to end at 1.2
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 remained the biggest loser as it
lost 50 cents to finish at 20.5 Singapore dollars. GE Life was
down 40 cents to end at 9 Singapore dollars and Robinson 24 cents
to close at 4.2 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said shares were lower as concerns lingered on among
players that the Singapore dollar might continue to be pressured
by fears of heavy investment losses by a member of the Brunei
royal family.
</P>
<P>
They also said concerns over Japan's reforms, notably its tax
reforms, also continued to discourage the market.
</P>
<P>
Commentators said shares were battered from their morning highs
to a lower close after Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said Singapore
was likely to slide into a recession in 1999.
</P>
<P>
They said Goh's comments affected the sentiment in the stock
market and sent the Singapore dollar sliding back toward the 1.7
to one U.S. dollar level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
