<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Firmer on Wall Street, Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket Tuesday
closed higher on positive leads from New York and Asia, but
investors still sought the safe haven of banks, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries closed up 17.5 points, or 0.64 percent, at
2769.3, off an intra-day high of 2771.7 and a low of 2750.6.
</P>
<P>
Dealer Hamish Dee of Henderson-Charlton Jones said the Dow
Jones Industrial Average, which gained 66.51 points, and a
stronger U.S. bond market helped the Australian bourse.
</P>
<P>
Asian markets, particularly Japan and Hong Kong, were also
higher, aiding the local market in the afternoon session.
</P>
<P>
Bank stocks were supported by the bond market, with National
Australia Bank gaining 32 cents to 22.3 Australian dollars and
Commonwealth Bank of Australia 35.1 cents to 19.691 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ Banking Group climbed 22 cents to 11.79 Australian dollars,
Westpac Banking Corp. rose 16.8 cents to 10.79 U.S. dollars and
St. George Bank gained 27.4 cents to 10.724 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Weaker commodity prices on the back of bearish news from Japan
curtailed the All Resources Index which closed up 1.7 points at
1073.2.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index finished 36.1 points higher at
4869.7.
</P>
<P>
The resources sector was mixed, with Australia's leading
company BHP down 16 cents, or 1.14 percent, at 13.92 Australian
dollars and global miner Rio Tinto up 37.9 cents at 19.03
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was weighed down early by the fall in gold
bullion prices in New York overnight, but it picked up off its
morning lows to close up 10 points at 1116.9.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trade in gold bullion gained 0.2 U.S. dollar to 293.65
U.S. dollars an ounce, which helped the gold index lift off its
lows.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 282.5 million shares valued at 613.69
million U.S. dollars, with rises outnumbering falls by 604 to 462.
 
</P>
