<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Little Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar meandered
aimlessly Tuesday in the wake of the long weekend in the United
States and a lack of firm reform news from Japan.
</P>
<P>
For the second consecutive day, the Australian dollar closed
little changed Tuesday, only marginally higher at 61.62 U.S. cents
from Monday's close of 61.56 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Peter Whitley, foreign exchange manager of Australia's Colonial
State Bank, said trading was very light as the foreign exchange
market went back into "hold mode."
</P>
<P>
"Japanese yen volumes were the lowest in about two months today
so it is not just Aussie, it is every currency," he said.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Banking Corp. Tuesday said it expected the besieged
Australian currency to crash through its record post-float low of
57.1 U.S. cents, reached in July 1986, to 55 U.S. cents during the
September quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Westpac's General Manager of economics Bill Evans said a
continued fall in commodities prices over the next six months
would be the negative factor for the unit.
</P>
<P>
"As markets become more disillusioned with Japan's lack of
commitment to genuine structural reform, the Australian dollar
will again come under pressure, due to further deterioration in
the commodity outlook," Evans said.
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney, the Australian dollar was buying 86.15
Japanese yen from 86.41 yen and 1.1177 German marks from 1.1187
marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
