<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Bank of China Bans Lottery-Attached Savings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC)
issued a circular today demanding all commercial bank and postal
savings banks to stop rewarded savings business, or a kind of
saving business attached with lottery.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the PBOC, this move is aimed to
standardize the operations of commercial banks, eliminate the
phenomenon of attracting savings with high interest, protect
depositors' legal rights and interests, and promote the service
quality of commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The circular demanded all commercial banks and credit
cooperatives to stop rewarded savings immediately.
</P>
<P>
This type of savings was first initiated in 1950 and was
stopped by the PBOC in 1960. Some financial institutions renewed
this practice in 1980 and the PBOC has since formulated some
relative rules.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the PBOC noted that the lottery-attached
savings have had some positive impact on the banking
industry. However, with the deposit business increasingly
competitive, various problems have arisen from rewarded deposits,
the spokesman said, leading to the decision to stop the business.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts to Harness Ulan Buh Desert Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Full-scale efforts are underway in
north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region to harness the Ulan
Buh Desert which was formerly the source of 150,000 cu.m. of sand
entering the Yellow River each year.
</P>
<P>
Shifting sand from the Ulan Buh (Mongolian words meaning red
bull) Desert also intruded and buried 250 hectares of nearby
farmland annually. The desert, the eighth largest in China, covers
one million hectares in the Bayannur League in western Inner
Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
A group of agricultural and forestry production and research
organizations, including six state-owned farms, have been formed
since the 1960s to tame the raging "red bull". However, the
large-scale campaign to harness the desert has only been in place
for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
In late 1996, the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region formed a
special leading group responsible for harnessing and developing
the Ulan Buh Desert in an all-round way.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region adopted an comprehensive plan to harness
the desert based on academic papers prepared by a group of
specialists sent to conduct research and devise execution measures.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2010, the desert control effort will transform
120,000 hectares of wasteland into cultivatable fields which will
produce an additional 440 million kg of grain and provide jobs for
80,000 surplus rural laborers, according to one desert control
expert.
</P>
<P>
The desert's forest cover will rise from the current 2.6
percent to 22.9 percent, the expert noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, related local governments have drafted wide-ranging
preferential policies to encourage desert control projects, with
related policies effectively attracting farsighted investors.
</P>
<P>
So far, approximately 30 Chinese and foreign investors have
provided investments of more than 100 million yuan (12 million US
dollars) for desert control and development efforts. Investors are
currently engaged farming and animal husbandry enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's 1998 Gold Output to reach 160 Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- China's gold output this year is
expected to exceed 160 tons, Wang Dexue, head of China's Gold
Administration, said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Gold production in China in the first five months of this year
was 28.3 percent higher than the same period last year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that China's actual gold output last year was 166.3
tons, making China the fifth largest gold-producing country after
South Africa, the United States, Australia and Canada.
</P>
<P>
China's production of gold has grown steadily for the past 20
years, with a yearly growth rate exceeding 10 percent, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
Wang attributed the increase in China's gold production to the
decline of gold prices in recent years which forced increased
production to maintain economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
He said that low gold prices also led non-government
enterprises to sell more gold to the state.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the cooperation between China and overseas
business people in the field of gold industry will be further
enhanced in the coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
