<HEADLINE> Asia Software Exhibition Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Software Development Asia
'98 (SDA '98) exhibition-cum-conference opened here Tuesday with
the theme of "Creating Waves in Asia's Software Development
Industry."
</P>
<P>
The economic uncertainty in the region does not seem to have
dampened support for the three-day event which has attracted a
record 42 local and foreign exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
The exhibitors put on show 60 products which may be of special
interest to applications, software, web and multimedia developers,
system administrators, applications developers, programmers,
software engineers and other information technology (IT)
professionals.
</P>
<P>
Opening the SDA '98, Malaysia's Science, Technology and
Environment Minister Law Hieng Ding called upon software
developers to intensify their efforts to capture the local market
for packaged software for which sales are expected to grow at an
annual rate of 17.4 percent until the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
He said the software market in Malaysia is lucrative despite
the economic gloom and the growth rate itself should result in a
final sales figure of 664.6 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Malaysia imports close to 2 billion
ringgit (about 500 million dollars) worth of software a year.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we in Malaysia must condition ourselves to assume
the lead in the production rather than just the consumption of
software," he said.
</P>
<P>
Funding for software development is also made available in
Malaysia through the Industry Grant Scheme (IGS) which is
allocated 100 million ringgit (about 25 million dollars), the
Multimedia Grant Scheme (MGS) with 50 million ringgit (about 12.5
million dollars) and Demonstrator Application Grant of 50 million
ringgit (about 12.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The total software market for the Asia Pacific region is
estimated at about 26 billion ringgit (about 6.341 billion
dollars) last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
