<HEADLINE> Palestinian, Israeli Officials Discuss Tensions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Senior Palestinian and Israeli
officers have held talks on defusing tensions in the Gaza Strip
after last week's standoff between Israeli troops and Palestinian
police, Israel Radio reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security chief in Gaza Mohammed Dahlan and head of
Israeli army's Southern Command Yom Tov Samia discussed for four
hours Monday night in Beersheba, southern Israel, on ways of
opening roads closed by Israel in the Gaza Strip to Palestinian
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Sources attending the meeting said the two sides reached an
understanding on several issues, though not an agreement.
</P>
<P>
They said the Palestinians and Israel agreed to tour the
disputed coastal road near the Gush Katif Jewish settlement in the
south of the Gaza Strip before deciding on any agreements.
</P>
<P>
Before the talks, Dahlan told reporters in Gaza that he was
hoping to seek a settlement that would allow the Palestinians to
freely use the coastal road.
</P>
<P>
The tensions began last Thursday when Palestinian police and
civilians blocked access to the settlement to protest against
Israeli closure of a section of the coastal road.
</P>
<P>
At the peak of the standoff, Israel sent tanks and armored
personnel carriers to reinforce key positions while Palestinian
police took fortified positions a short distance away.
</P>
<P>
The two sides ended the standoff Friday after intensive
mediation by the United States and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jewish settlers in the Gaza Strip said on Monday
that if the Israeli army opens the coastal road to the
Palestinians, they will respond by blocking roads in the West Bank
and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said that it closed some roads in the Gaza Strip,
including the coastal road, merely for "security reasons." The
Palestinians have strongly opposed the move, which they said has
violated the agreements signed between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has said the
standoff was "a provocative act from the Palestinian side." The
Palestinians, in return, have accused Israel of "preparing for
war." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
