<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Sets Conditions for Water to Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Tuesday that his country has agreed in
principle to supply water to Singapore but with conditions.
</P>
<P>
"We have assured them that we will give them the water but
there must be conditions to supplying water," he told a press
conference after opening a two-day international conference on
corporate governance here.
</P>
<P>
Without specifying the conditions, Mahathir said, "In principle
we have reached agreement. We just couldn't reach agreement on the
details."
</P>
<P>
"As you know, even between the states in Malaysia it's so
difficult to resolve the problem of supplying water from one state
to another," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was asked to comment on his meeting with his Singapore
counterpart, Goh Chok Tong, here in February during which they
reportedly discussed the water supply issue.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Foreign Minister S. Jayakumar told the parliament
last week that several outstanding issues in Singapore-Malaysia
bilateral relations remained unresolved, including the water
supply issue in which Singapore was reported to have sought
legally binding conditions when the present two agreements expire
in 2011 and 2061.
</P>
<P>
Singapore gets about half of its daily water needs from
Malaysia's Johor State under the two existing agreements.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "Points of agreement are points of agreement but
treaties are different matters. The points of agreement have yet
to be ratified. We don't ratify them either at the cabinet level
or at the parliamentary level. This involves relations of two
countries and we cannot just change treaties without reference to
parliament."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the water supply issue was related to the
Singapore Central Provident Fund (CPF) issue involving about
200,000 Malaysians working in Singapore, Mahathir said he could
not see how the two issues could be related.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday the Malaysian cabinet urged Singapore to allow
peninsular Malaysians, who no longer worked in the republic or
were retrenched, to withdraw their savings from the CPF which
reportedly is holding more than 1 billion ringgit (about 250
million U.S. dollars) in Malaysian workers' savings and only
allows peninsular Malaysians full withdrawal upon reaching 55
years of age. However, those from Sabah and Sarawak, East
Malaysia, can withdraw their savings upon completion of employment
contracts in Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
