<HEADLINE> Hui Nationality and Islamic Studies Thrive in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The study of the Chinese Hui
nationality and the culture of Islam has made great advances in
many fields of research during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
China has now more than 10 research institutes and several
hundred scholars engaged in the study of the Hui nationality, said
Yu Zhengui, an authority on the Hui nationality and president of
the Ningxia Academy of Social Sciences, adding that a number of
masters and doctorate degrees have been awarded in this field.
</P>
<P>
The Hui people are ethnic group formed through the integration
of ancient Persian, Arab and Chinese peoples. With a population of
9 million, the Hui rank as the third largest Chinese ethnic
minority group, found all over the country, but mainly in the
northwest.
</P>
<P>
As China's sole provincial-level autonomous region of the Hui
nationality, Ningxia has formed a special institute specializing in
the study of the Hui nationality and Islam.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the research staff has delivered 500 theses
and compiled many books on the study of Hui society. The Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region also sponsors a national periodical on Hui
studies, and the region has become the center of Hui study in China.
</P>
<P>
Yu Zhengui said that Hui studies has expanded into history and
various aspects besides Islam, covering ethnic customs,
architecture, medicine, population, language and sports, with a
large number of publications now available.
</P>
<P>
China's Hui studies has begun to expand outside of the
country. The research institute in Ningxia has made extensive
exchanges with foreign academic organizations and experts
including those in Saudi Arabia, Turkey, the United States and
Britain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
