<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Southern China Backs HK Shipping Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong official said here
Tuesday that the rapid economic growth in southern China would be
strong backing for Hong Kong to maintain its position as a
regional shipping center.
</P>
<P>
In an opening address at the Tripartite Shippers' Councils
meeting, Stephen Ip, secretary for economic services, said, "Hong
Kong is fortunate enough to be situated right next to the Pearl
River Delta, one of the fastest growing economic areas in the
region."
</P>
<P>
Ip noted that the strong export and import demand of the
numerous manufacturing centers in the Pearl River Delta has
supported the rapid growth of Hong Kong as the main port for South
China.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been the world's busiest container port for six
years in a row, handling 14.5 million twenty-foot equivalent units
(TEUs) of containers in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is also the world's largest international air freight
center. The old Kai Tak Airport handled 1.79 million tons of cargo
in 1997, while the new Chek Lap Kok airport, opened for commercial
aviation on Monday, is able to handle up to 3 million tons of
cargo each year at the initial stage.
</P>
<P>
According to the secretary for economic services, Hong Kong
will start to construct a new container terminal, CT 9, later this
year and the first berth is expected to come into use in late
2001. With six berths, the new terminal is designed to handle 2.6
million TEUs when it is fully completed in 2004.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong now is building its first river trade terminal to
handle the increasing volumes of cargo from southern China.
Starting from October 1998, the terminal will go into operation in
phases and will eventually handle 1.3 million TEUs of containers a
year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting brought together three of the most influential
shippers bodies in Asia, namely the Hong Kong, Japan and South
Korea Shippers' Councils.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0167 </DOCNO>
