<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Stock Boom Creates Another Billionaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Yahoo co-founder Jerry Yang, a
Chinese-American, reached billionaire status Tuesday as a result
of Internet stock boom.
</P>
<P>
Yang, 29, became the latest Net executive to gain entry into
the billionaire boys club as Yahoo's opening price climbed to 178.875
U.S. dollars. He holds 5.7 million shares, or a 12.2 percent
stake in the Silicon Valley company.
</P>
<P>
Yahoo's other co-founder, David Filo, was just one step ahead
of Yang into the club. The 32-year-old executive, who holds nearly
5.9 million Yahoo shares, reached billionaire status last week.
</P>
<P>
The company's stock has been on a rocket ride since early June,
when it traded slightly above 100 dollars a share. In fact, it
repeatedly has set new 52-week highs, with Tuesday marking the
latest peak.
</P>
<P>
Yang ended the day with paper wealth of 1.14 billion dollars,
while Filo's net worth stood at 1.2 billion dollars, based on
Yahoo's closing price of 199.25 dollars per share.
</P>
<P>
Before them, the founder of the online bookstore Amazon.com,
Jeff Bezos, cracked the one-billion-dollar barrier in early June,
when Amazon.com stock hit 51.25 dollars per share. Bezos, 34, who
holds 19.8 million of his company's shares, was worth 2.8 billion
dollars on paper Tuesday, based on the company's closing price of
139.5 dollars a share.
</P>
<P>
Both Amazon and Yahoo were founded in 1994. Yahoo hit the
public markets in April 1996, while Amazon went public in May of
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
