<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Don't Politicize Mines Sale, Trade Union Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Congress of Trade Union
President Fackson Shamenda has warned that the privatization of
the country's main foreign exchange earner, copper mines, should
not be politicized because doing so will be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Tuesday quoted him as saying here on Monday
that Zambians have to take a painful decision on the sale of the
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) and avoid indecision.
</P>
<P>
He said "indecision was what brought our economy down during
the UNIP (former ruling party) era and this mistake must be
avoided at all costs."
</P>
<P>
When selling the mines, market forces have to determine the
pricing, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the mines are currently at their lowest production and
are a drain on the economy of the country.
</P>
<P>
President Frederick Chiluba reiterated last Saturday that his
country will sell its copper mines in full value.
</P>
<P>
Zambia discontinued the negotiations last April with Kafue
consortium on the sale of Nchanga and Nkana mines, which make up
65 percent of the ZCCM assets, over disagreement on the prices of
the two mines.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, two other foreign mining companies pulled out, citing
falling international copper prices as the main reason for their
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Last month, donors pledged Zambia an aid of 530 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, some donors said recently that they will not release
the pledged aid until ZCCM is privatized because the money ZCCM
is losing equals the amount of the aid the donor community
pledged to give Zambia and that if it is released, it will go to
bailing out the ailing ZCCM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
