<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Parliament Doubts Government's Report of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian parliament has cast
doubt on the government's report of the country's high economic
growth, planning a probe into the situation.
</P>
<P>
The parliament has found the government has reported a
situation much higher than those by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank said Jordan's economy grew at a rate below 1
percent for 1996 and at 2.5 to 3 percent for 1997, while the
government figures put the two years' rates at 5.2 and 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Economic and Finance Committee at the Lower
House of Parliament Ali Abul Ragheb was quoted by Jordan's
official news agency Petra Tuesday as saying the committee
considers the discrepancies as a "serious issue."
</P>
<P>
The committee plans to convene several meetings in the coming
two weeks with private and public sector officials to discern the
"reality of the economic situation in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a top priority for the parliament," said Ragheb. "We
are not trying to create a scandal out of this issue but to reach
a conclusion on the country's economic growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to find out who is responsible for this and minimize
the negative consequences of this issue," Ragheb added.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister for Development and Minister of Foreign
Affairs Jawad Anani earlier admitted such inconsistencies, but
denied that the government tried to conceal real economic growth
indicators.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Razzaq Bani Hani, director of the research department at
the Jordanian Ministry of Planning, has said that Jordan's
economy declined in real terms in the past two years and the World
Bank's figures are "more reasonable."
</P>
<P>
Hani attributed Jordan's economic decline to the recent
political developments in the region, namely, the deadlock in the
Mideast peace process and the decrease in Jordan's exports to Iraq
and other Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
Some private sector representatives have said that such
"serious distortions" could undermine Jordan's credibility,
especially with regard to the 1989-98 economic reform program
structured by the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The two international organizations have provided the kingdom
with millions of U.S. dollars in loans and grants under this
program to revive the kingdom's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
