<HEADLINE> Minister: Malaysia's Growth Target Needs to Be Revised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim said Tuesday that the
country's 2 to 3 percent growth projection for 1998 needs to be
revised.
</P>
<P>
But he did not mention any new figure, saying it would be
announced soon.
</P>
<P>
"But the government will try to stimulate the economy by
establishing new funds and through other measures," he told
reporters after officiating at the 1999 budget dialogue with the
theme "Toward Engineering a Speedy and Sustainable Economic
Recovery" here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Anwar hoped that the country would not go to register negative
growth for this year, saying, "We are looking at the figures and
want to know how fast can the (country's latest) stimulus package
be implemented."
</P>
<P>
Toward this end, he said, it is very critical that all agencies
and departments take measures to speed up the implementation of
projects and approvals.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that during the current economic slowdown, daily
meetings were held between him and Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
as "we work effectively as one team."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia registered a negative growth of 1.8 percent for the
first quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
Anwar announced in mid-June a stimulus package, setting aside
7.031 billion ringgit (about 1.793 billion U.S. dollars) as
supplementary budget allocation in an effort to generate real
gross domestic product growth. 
</P>
