<HEADLINE> Ugandan Mayor to Apply for Bail in Boston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Kampala City Mayor Nasser
Sebaggalla will apply for his bail in a Boston federal court
Tuesday after his case was shifted there from New York last week.
</P>
<P>
The embattled mayor is hoping that he will be granted leave to
return to Uganda after this detention hearing as he is waiting
for the full trial, the Monitor daily said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala is charged with depositing altered checks worth
329,000 U.S. Dollars in his personal account in Bank Boston as
early as early 1997 and making false statements to Customs
officers about the amount of cash he was carrying.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to plead not guilty to all the charges against
him, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The hearing, expected to be presided over by U.S. Magistrate
Judge, Marianne Bowler, is supposed to determine whether the
mayor should be detained pending his criminal trial later this
year or be allowed to remain under conditions in the United
States or be permitted to return to Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Sabaggala was arrested at John F. Kennedy Airport in New York
on June 13 when he was to board a flight en route to Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Back in Uganda, there is an outcry for his stepping down from
the top position of the capital not only because of this scandal,
but also because of his inadequate academic qualifications
required of the post.
</P>
<P>
He was made mayor in April in a contraversial election in
which he was accused of being unable to speak good English and
not possessing an A level certificate. 
</P>
