<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Kenyan Coffee Houses Return to Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Eight leading Kenyan coffee
houses, suspended from last week's coffee export auction, have
been allowed to return to the weekly auction opening Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Mild Coffee Trade Association (MCTA)
received apologies from the eight members which, according to
industry sources, had criticized the association's performance,
newspapers published here reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The management committee, having taken into consideration the
unconditional apologies received from all the suspended members,
decided to lift the suspension," the MCTA said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Since the suspensions have been lifted, they will participate
in Tuesday's auction," said a spokesman for the Coffee Board of
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The suspended coffee traders were Cetco, C.Dorman, Taylor
Winch, Pati, Ibero Kenya Ltd, Green Coffee, Gourmet and Hans
Sickmuller, according to the MCTA.
</P>
<P>
The row with the MCTA began two months ago when some coffee
houses told a visiting delegate from the International Coffee
Organization (ICO) that their interests were not adequately
represented by the MCTA.
</P>
<P>
The delegate made those views known at a sitting of the ICO
and also argued that those Kenyan trade houses not satisfied with
the MCTA could obtain additional private representation.
</P>
<P>
These views filtered back to the MCTA, which felt deeply
offended. The association wrote to 17 individual companies asking
them to confirm if they share those views. Those which replied in
the affirmative or did not reply were barred from last week's
auction.
</P>
<P>
The market average at last week's coffee auction was posted by
the Kenya Coffee Auctions Ltd at 117.12 U.S. Dollars per bag
weighing 50 kilograms for sale, sharply down from 148.87 Dollars
per bag in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the suspended coffee houses represent about 70
percent of the foreign coffee trade in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is one of the world's leading producers of quality
premium Arabica coffees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
