<HEADLINE> France to Recognize Palestinian State: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- France has decided to recognize a
Palestinian state if it is declared after the interim agreement
between the Palestinians and Israel ends next May, a report on the
Israeli Ha'aretz newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted sources in Paris as saying that the decision
was made with a consensus among France's top leaders, including
President Jacques Chirac, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
They said the French leaders have emphasized that a Palestinian
state is first of all a "legitimate result" of the Middle East
peace process and a vested right of the Palestinians under the
principle of self-determination.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry so far has refused to comment on
the issue, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
But a spokesman for the ministry has stressed that France has
always been positively looking on the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state, it added.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has said he will declare an
independent Palestinian state next May whether or not a final
peace agreement is reached with Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has threatened to
annex part of the West Bank if the Palestinians take the action.
</P>
</TEXT>
