<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 115 Killed in Banditry Raids in Northeastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-seven security officers and
88 civilians have been killed in bandit and cattle rustling
violence in the Northeastern Province of Kenya in the last three
years, governmental reports indicate.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the government show that the 115 people
died in a total of 414 bandit assaults between January 1995 and
May this year, the Kenya Time newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The slain officers -- including two inspectors -- died while
pursuing bandits in bomb and land-mine blasts or when their
stations were attacked by gunmen, who at times comprised
militiamen from war-torn Somalia, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The civilians either died after they were shot by bandits or
fell to the crossfire between police and bandits in the vast arid
province.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, three civilians who were acting as scouts for
security officers pursuing bandits in Garissa District, were
slain by bandits who went on to slaughter nine police officers.
</P>
<P>
The official data also indicate that the rate of slaughter of
security officers escalated in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 27 late offices, 14 law enforcement officers were
shot dead in action in Wajir and Garissa districts last year
alone and another four were shot dead this year.
</P>
<P>
Cumulative economic losses caused by all the bandit attacks
were estimated to reach about 3.8 million Shillings (64,400 U.S.
Dollars), said the report.
</P>
<P>
More than 6,000 head of livestocks were taken away by the
rustlers during the period and nearly one-third of them were
recovered later.  
</P>
</TEXT>
