<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Grain Bases to Adopt Unified Pricing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Four leading grain producers in
northeast and northern China are expected to introduce unified
minimum market grain prices in September this year in an attempt
to avoid underselling or price wars on the grain market.
</P>
<P>
The four areas -- Heilongjiang, Jilin and Liaoning provinces
and Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region -- agreed to set the minimum
market price at 1,200 yuan (145 US dollars) per metric ton for
maize and 1,600 yuan (193 US dollars) per metric ton for rice.
</P>
<P>
Grain enterprises will be permitted to adjust prices in
accordance with market operations and internal management
condition.
</P>
<P>
The four areas have pledged to hold regular meetings for an
exchange of information on development in pricing, grain purchases
and management. A grain coordination conference will be held in
September in China's northermost Heilongjiang Province to discuss
grain prices for the fourth quarter and fixed quotas for this
year's purchases.
</P>
<P>
The four areas harvested more than 85 million tons of cereals
in 1996, or 17 percent of the national total. The areas also
account for some 75 percent of maize in storage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
