<HEADLINE> India to Set up Information Technology Center in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- India is soon to establish an
information technology center for Africa in Zimbabwe, The Daily
Herald reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The center, to be based in Harare, will be under an agreement
of the Group of 15 developing countries, which seeks to spearhead
cooperation and development among them. The south-south
cooperation is also meant to supplement, and complement domestic
programs.
</P>
<P>
In an interview Monday, India's Deputy High Commissioner to
Zimbabwe Pavel J. Diengdoh said her government had already
provided a pre-feasibility report on the center prepared by the
Indian National Center for software technology in consultation
with the country's department of electronics.
</P>
<P>
India would provide training, equipment and personnel for the
center, while Zimbabwe was expected to provide land, and meet
building costs.
</P>
<P>
The center would also contribute to the creation of a strong
human resources base for Africa, specializing in computer
software. Information technology is sweeping across the world,
and its impact will be no less than that of the industrial
revolution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
