<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Lake Selected As Model Scenic Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- West Lake, a famous tourism resort
in Hangzhou, has been selected as one of China's ten model scenic
zones with a higher-degree of civilization and cultural
development.
</P>
<P>
The zone, which is hemmed in green hills from three sides,
covers 60 square kilometers in the central part of Hangzhou in
east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The West Lake Scenic Zone boasts more than 100 scenic sites,
which draw over 12 million domestic visitors and 400,000 tourists
from overseas annually.
</P>
<P>
The local government has extended great efforts since early in
the 1980s to clean the formerly heavily-polluted lake.
</P>
<P>
For example, in the late 1980s, Hangzhou completed a 3,100 meter
diversion pipeline to pump water from the Qiantang River into the
lake. The system has a 300,000 cu.m. daily pumping capacity and
has diverted more than 150 million cu.m. of water since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the area north of West Lake has been transformed
into a scenic corridor stretching three kilometers. The corridor
features six small scenic sites and landscaped areas covering
90,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The city has extended great efforts to both develop the
environment and provide high-quality tourism services. With the
support of the city government, Hangzhou residents have in recent
years aroused several thousand volunteers to involved themselves
into actions to protect greenery in the West Lake area.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the city government again initiated public welfare
activities to do something to beautify tourists boats and yachts
and tourist spots around the lake, and the lightings on the lake
have been re-aligned this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Draws Disaster-Toll Reduction Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will complete the
formation of an action plan to reduce the human and economic costs
of natural disasters by June next year, The Daily Star newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The action plan will include 416 separate disaster control
plans for 340 unions in 16 of the country's 64 districts, which
cover all the cyclone-, flood- and drought-prone areas.
</P>
<P>
Disaster preparedness specialist Khan Chowdhury presented a
draft plan at a workshop held here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The disaster action plan is part of the project titled "Support
to Comprehensive Disaster Management."
</P>
<P>
The entire project will cost 210 million taka (about 4.47
million U.S. dollars), which will be jointly financed by the
Bangladesh government and two U.N. agencies.
</P>
<P>
The plan aims to increase awareness of the risks of natural
calamities and the practical possibilities for reducing human and
economic risks through action at households community union and
sub-district levels.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the plan also aims to improve local warning
dissemination systems in relation to cyclone and flood, and to
implement local plans for evacuation, rescue, relief and initial
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Tropical cyclone, drought and flood are the country's major
natural calamities, which have caused massive losses to the
national economy every year.
</P>
<P>
Some 42 percent of the country's land and 43 percent of its
population were affected during the 1979 drought period and some
10 major tornadoes during 1969-91 claimed thousands of lives in
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 died in 1970 in a cyclone alone, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenyang Growing into Communications Hub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang, the capital of northeast
Liaoning Province, has emerged as a major communications hub in
northeast China over recent years.
</P>
<P>
Some 350 transportation routes link the city with 65 cities in
10 Chinese provinces, according to a provincial highway official.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang has maintained its status as the largest economic
center in the region by allocating more than 610 million yuan
(73.5 million US dollars) to construct a highway network which
includes 13 bus stations with total floor space approaching
420,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The Wu'ai Bus Station, the largest facility of its kind in
China which includes a passenger terminal, cargo handling facility
and an underground parking lot, was constructed a cost of 100
million yuan (12 million US dollars). The station serves 300,000
passengers daily and has an annual cargo handling capacity of
200,000 tons of cargo, with convenient services offered to 50
cities in 10 provinces.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the city plans to enlarge and
restructure existing cargo stations in four counties and open
express cargo services from Shenyang to Dalian and Beijing later
this year.
</P>
<P>
Plans through the year 2000 call for the establishment of four
to five regional information networks, an express passenger
network covering northeastern China, 39 coordinated rail, highway
and sea container transport routes, and 210 city cargo truck
routes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
