<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinopec Incorporates Guangdong Oil Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The China National Petrochemical
Corporation (Sinopec), one of China's designated petrochemical
leaders, is continuing to vigorously implement its expansion plan
in south China.
</P>
<P>
Sinopec formally incorporated 116 oil firms in Guangdong
Province in a Monday ceremony held in Guangzhou, the provincial
capital.
</P>
<P>
China is currently implementing a plan to form two major oil
conglomerates -- the China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC)
and the Sinopec. The former will control the exploration and
production of oil and gas, with the latter focusing on production
of petrochemicals.
</P>
<P>
Sinopec Vice-chairman Zhang Jiaren said the new Guangdong
Provincial Petroleum Group Co. will continue the commitment to
supply the local oil products market, the largest market of its
kind in China.
</P>
<P>
The restructed petroleum firms in Guangdong have a total
workforce of 20,000 people, with combined assets of five billion
yuan (602 million US dollars) and sales revenue of 10 billion yuan
(1.2 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The State Council's reform plan calls for CNPC and Sinopec
to control all of the nation's oil and gas fields, oil refineries,
petrochemical enterprises and fueling stations.
</P>
<P>
The Sinopec's business activities will focus on eastern and
southern parts of the country, with the CNPC concentrating on
northern and western China.
</P>
<P>
The CNPC incorporated all oil companies and fueling stations in
southwest China's Sichuan Province in early June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
