<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Female Magistrate for Yi Nationality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Chunxiu was recently elected as
the magistrate for Mianning County in the Liangshan Yi Autonomous
Prefecture in southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, a native of Ganluo County, became the first female
magistrate from the Yi nationality and also the youngest women
from any ethnic group elected to the post.
</P>
<P>
Zhu graduated from the Southwest China Institute for
Nationalities in 1984, and served as deputy head of Mianning
County beginning in 1993.
</P>
<P>
She won resounding voter support from members of the Yi
nationality, as well as other ethnic groups and members of the Han
nationality.
</P>
<P>
Members of the nationality, the sixth largest ethnic group in
China, live mostly in Sichuan, Yunnan and Guizhou provinces. The
Liangshan Yi Autonomous Prefecture, located in the southwestern
part of Sichuan Province, has a total population of 3.82 million
people, including over 1.6 million Yi.
</P>
<P>
The slave system existed in the prefecture until the 1950s
when the Chinese government launched democratic reform and engaged
in peaceful consultations.
</P>
<P>
The government has not only helped the Yi promote economic
development, but has also established institutes for minority
nationalities and sponsored courses for members of ethnic
groups. The Liangshan Prefecture is currently home to 13
institutes of higher education.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that ethnic cadre account for 46 percent of
leading group at different level of government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
