<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Defaulted Loans at 2.28 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The defaulted loans with Bangladesh's
four nationalized commercial banks totaled 107.27 billion taka
(2.28 billion U.S. dollars) up to May this year, newspapers here
reported Tuesday, quoting Finance Minister S.A.M.S. Kabria.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 87.97 billion taka (1.87 billion dollars) has been
recovered in cash and 28.90 billion taka (615 million dollars)
re-scheduled since December 1996, Kabria told parliament Monday.
</P>
<P>
The huge amount of defaulted bank loans was accumulated over
the years, and it has seriously affected the national economy in a
number of ways, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
On the defaulted loan recovery drive, task forces were formed
in all of the country's banks to monitor the progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government had also made necessary amendments to the Money
loan Court Act, the Bank Company Act and the bankruptcy Act to
expedite the recovery of defaulted loans, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government would take more effective legal and
administrative measures to expedite the recovery of defaulted bank
loans in accordance with the existing laws, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
