<HEADLINE> SriLanka to Start Documenting All Artifacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Archaeological
department, in a bid to put a stop to the loss of archaeological
treasures in the country, will soon start documenting all
artifacts, the department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It said records indicate that millions of dollars worth of
artifacts are smuggled out of Sri Lanka annually.
</P>
<P>
Under the department's plan, Dambadeniya in North Western
Province has been selected as the first location for this
exercise. The task will be a long-drawn-out process and may need
at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The government also seeks foreign assistance. Britain will send
two archaeological experts to Sri Lanka to help local experts, and
financial and other types of assistance including equipment will
be available later, the department said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the department has purchased equipment worth about
50,000 U.S. dollars for this purpose. 
</P>
