<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Stock Market Index Down 42.78 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Caracas Stock Market Index was
down 42.78 percent in the first six months of the year, a market
research company, known as Metroeconomica, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In June alone, Metroeconomica said in its monthly report, the
index of the Caracas Stock Market, one of the three in Venezuela,
dropped 19.85 percent from May, and 46.59 percent from June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The index was brought down by the impact of the ongoing
financial crisis in Southeast Asia and the deep plunge of oil
prices at the world market, where Venezuela has a major stake.
</P>
<P>
As the second largest oil producer within the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), Venezuela's oil industry
serves as one of the pillars of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Since the downturn of Asian economies in October 1997, however,
prices for Venezuelan crude slipped from last year's average 16.49
dollars per barrel to the current level of less than 10 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Given the circumstances, in Asia and on the oil market,
analysts said, the uncertainty in this Latin American country's
stock market is likely to last through 1998, or into early 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
