<HEADLINE> hke - Italian Police Recover Stolen Paintings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian police recovered on Monday
three Van Gogh and Cezanne paintings stolen from the National
Gallery of Modern Art in Rome 48 days ago.
</P>
<P>
While recovering the priceless art works, the police arrested
eight people, including a woman employee of the gallery, in early
morning operations carried out in Rome and Turin.
</P>
<P>
Noting that "a bleeding wound" was closed, Deputy Prime
Minister and Cultural Minister Walter Veltroni told a news
conference that the paintings would be exhibited in the gallery
from Tuesday, still in places where they were stolen.
</P>
<P>
The theft took place on May 19, when masked gunmen bound the
guards and then snatched "The Gardener" and "L'Arlesienne" by Van
Gogh, and "Le Cabanon de Jourdan" by Cezanne.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the police described the process of retrieving the
stolen paintings a "difficult and risky operation," as they had to
make sure not to damage the works.
</P>
<P>
Besides the paintings, weapons and drugs were also found in the
houses of the arrested suspects, seven of them having previous
crime convictions.
</P>
<P>
The investigation was still under way as eight other people
were suspected of being involved in the case, the police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
