<HEADLINE> Drug Control Workshop Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A national training workshop under a
six-country memorandum of understanding for sub-regional
collaboration on drug control is being held here to strengthen the
capacity of signatory countries in project design and management.
</P>
<P>
The six-country MOU on control of illicit drug trafficking and
abuse in the sub-region, involving China, Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar,
Thailand and Vietnam as well as the United Nations Drug Control
Program (UNDCP), was initiated in October 1993 at the U.N.
Headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
The seven-day training workshop, which began on Monday, is
sponsored by the Myanmar Central Committee for Drug Abuse Control
and the UNDCP.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, aimed at improving skills of the participants in
project design and management, covers project identification,
formulation and appraisal as well as implementation and
management, the official New Light of Myanmar reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In July 1997, the six countries' ministerial and senior
officials held a meeting on drug abuse and control in Bangkok,
Thailand, during which 11 projects on law enforcement, supply
reduction and demand reduction were established with agreements on
three projects on law enforcement signed.
</P>
<P>
Attending the workshop, conducted by a UNDCP team of
international consultants and experts, are national staff members
at management levels of counterpart agencies and associated
institutions in the central and provincial governments of Myanmar.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
