<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Moves to Ease Credit Squeeze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- With greater exchange rate
stability in the past few months, Thailand is moving to ease the
credit crunch in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The baht has been holding steady around 41 to the U.S. dollar,
enabling the government to gradually increase liquidity in the
market, said officials from the Bank of Thailand, the central
bank.
</P>
<P>
The baht traded on Monday at 39.91/41.70 to the dollar, up
slightly from 41.45/41.55 quoted last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The situation has allowed the Bank of Thailand to buy a
"significant" share of one-year bonds auctioned by the Financial
Institutions Development Fund (FIDF), a move expected to increase
cash availability.
</P>
<P>
The auctioned bonds are worth 10 billion baht (250 million
dollars) in two lots starting late last month. The government says
as much as 500 billion baht (12.5 billion dollars) in long-term
bonds will be sold to help restructure funding costs for the FIDF,
which is now dependent on the short-term market for funds.
</P>
<P>
The fund has run up liabilities exceeding 1.1 trillion baht (27
billion dollars) over the past year from its support for ailing
finance companies and banks. The huge demand for capital has
helped push short-term interest rates upwards, as local financial
institutions lend excess liquidity to the fund through the bond
repurchase market.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the liquidity crunch, Thailand needs 26.1 billion
dollars in capital inflow over the next 12 months. From October
1996 to February this year, Thailand lost 12 billion dollars
through capital flight and over next 12 months, Thailand will have
to repay 6.1 billion dollars of short-term foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Another 8 billion dollars will be needed to repay Bank of
Thailand's swap obligations.
</P>
<P>
In the first bonds auction held by the FIDF, the accepted
yield-to-maturity was 15 percent and fell to 14.7 percent for the
second round last week. Yield bids ranged from 12.75 to 18.75
percent in the first round, and 12.75 percent to 17.5 percent for
the second, according to a statement from Bank of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
It said regulators have relied on setting interest rates
through the bond repurchase market as a key instrument in
supporting the baht, as higher interest rates increase the
benefits of holding baht instead of dollars.
</P>
<P>
But greater stability in exchange rates has allowed the central
bank to gradually ease interest rates in the market. Bank
authorities said caution is needed in cutting down rates to avoid
upsetting the baht, spurring capital flight and fueling inflation.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Chatumongol Sonakul said that as exchange
and interest rates stabilize with market forces, the central bank
has greater flexibility to adjust liquidity in the system.
</P>
<P>
He said the latest review by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) gave the green light to the central bank to ease monetary
policies and pump 50 billion baht (1.25 billion dollars) into the
system.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange rate is moving in a way it should. The central
bank's policy is to pump more money into the system, but it has to
be done gradually and in line with investment demand," Chatumongol
said.
</P>
<P>
"There is some investor demand for money for favorable business
prospects. But overall investment is still depressed while
consumption remains," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF program calls for reserve money to expand to 471
billion baht (11.7 billion dollars) by the end of September, and
505-512 billion baht (12.6-12.8 billion dollars) by the end of
this year. At the end of the first quarter, reserve money was 451
billion baht (11.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Even so, injecting additional funds was only a short-term
measure to ease the credit crunch, bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
Given this situation, regulators were proceeding with medium-
and long-term measures to reform the financial system. Open market
operations, where the central bank purchases or sells securities
in the market to manipulate liquidity and interest rates, would
also be developed.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is said to favor using bond market
intervention to help achieve economic targets, a monetary policy
model similar to that used by the Reserve Bank of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand has been able to maintain low inflation and develop
a competitive bond market through its model. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Tourism Takes Steep Dive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian tourism took a steep
dive with tourist arrivals in the first five months of this year
38 percent less than the same period last year, the Cambodian
Tourism Ministry said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It said about 83,000 visitors arrived at Pochentong Airport in
the five months, compared with 134,000 visitors in the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The sharp decline is caused by violence in the Southeast Asian
country, particularly in the capital Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has seen a fast growth in Cambodia in recent years,
with 220,000 tourist arrivals in 1996. But growth came to a sudden
halt in July 1997 when fighting broke out between the two
premiers, Hun Sen and Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
Though industry insiders expects a full recovery of tourism in
October, much depends on the outcome of the July 26 general
elections.
</P>
<P>
Tourism operators believe foreign travellers would come back if
stability and security could be restored after the elections. But
their hopes could fail if the elections don't go smoothly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
