<HEADLINE> Kosovo Issue Remains Priority, Says OSCE Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The solution to the Kosovo crisis
has become a priority for the whole international community,
including the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE), Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek said in Sarajevo
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Geremek, who is the present OSCE chairman, told reporters that
the crisis could endanger peace and stability in the whole Balkan
area.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE is the first organization to put forward a way to
resolve the crisis in the southern Yugoslav province of Kosovo
which is acceptable to both Serbian and ethnic Albanian sides,
Geremek said.
</P>
<P>
This solution would confirm the integrity of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia as well as ensuring compliance with the
justified demands of Kosovo ethnic Albanians, especially those
relating to a special status for Kosovo, the Polish foreign
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We demand an immediate cessation of violence and conflicts,
the beginning of fair negotiations and a debate on the special
status of Kosovo," he said. 
