<HEADLINE> Yunnan Province Enhances Protection of Wild Animals (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Ji Xuebing, a farmer in Binchuan
County, southwest China's Yunnan Province, recently discovered
that the eagle's nest on the roof of his house contained five
apparently abandoned fledglings.
</P>
<P>
Ji and his family soon realized that the mother had been
missing for several days and immediately fed the starving birds.
</P>
<P>
The young eagles learned to fly within four months and Ji
decided to set them free in a nearby forest.
</P>
<P>
An official of Yunnan Provincial Protection Center for Wild
Animals noted that local residents exhibit the same concern as Ji
by protecting thousands of wild animals, including wild birds,
bears and elephants.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the province strictly abides by the Law on
the Protection of Wild Animals which prohibits sales of wild
species.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, two men were severely punished for killing wild
elephants in the tropical forests in south China's Xishuangbanna.
</P>
<P>
The care Yunnan citizens show for wild animals can also be seen
in their love for red-bill gulls from Siberia.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of gulls flock to Kunming, the provincial
capital, in both winter and spring. Local residents welcome the
birds with both food and medical care if needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
