<HEADLINE> Yunnan Province Enhances Protection of Wild Animals (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Yunnan Animal Protection Association has organized
a number of campaigns to promote a greater understanding of the
need to protect and the relationship between human beings and wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan Province is home to 1,731 vertebrates species, or 54
percent of the total number of related species in China.
</P>
<P>
A number of species, including Asian elephants, golden monkeys,
Indochina tigers and green peacocks, are under world-class
protection.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has opened 108 nature reserves covering 2.02 million
hectares, or five percent of the province's total land area. The
province strictly prohibits hunting in the reserves, according to
a local official.
</P>
<P>
The province also established over a dozen shelters which are
currently providing treatment for more than 20,000 animals or
birds, said one local official, adding that most animals are
eventually set free.
</P>
<P>
Extensive protection efforts have promoted a significant
increase in the number of wild animals, with statistics from
related departments showing that the number of elephants has grown
from 60 only a few years ago to 250 today, the number of golden
monkeys has jumped to over 600 and the population of green
peacocks has surpassed 1,000 birds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia: Eyes on China, Russia for Coffee Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's National
Coffee Federation plans to spend one million U.S. dollars to
promote its market share in China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The funding, said the trade association on Monday, would boost
Colombia's coffee sales in the two countries and help offset the
decreasing demands on the European and U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
While coffee consumption in Europe and the United States is
down 1.4 percent on annual basis, the crop's output is on the rise
worldwide, forcing the association to look for other markets.
</P>
<P>
In China and Russia, where great market potentials are yet to
be tapped, coffee producing countries altogether have already
spent 10 million dollars on promotional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's National Coffee Federation alone contributed one
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In China, the average coffee consumption is one cup per person
a year now. But given the country's large population of over 1.2
billion, the sales will get better.
</P>
<P>
In Russia, average consumption is 131 cups of coffee per year.
</P>
<P>
Coffee producing countries, which consider 1998 as a bad year
with plunging international prices, hope promotions will bring up
their sales in China and Russia to international standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
