<HEADLINE> India Denies Re-think on Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government claimed
Monday that there was no change in its basic position on what it
calls the discriminatory nature of the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Indian press has indicated lately that the government's
position on the CTBT is shifting from criticism toward
consideration of joining if certain concessions in technology
transfer are secured.
</P>
<P>
The country was currently in the process of conveying this view
to the "key interlocutors," said a major Indian newspaper, the
Hindustan Times.
</P>
<P>
However, the Press Trust of India (PTI), in dismissing the
conclusion as premature, quoted official sources as saying that
India's basic position on the issue "remains unaltered."
</P>
<P>
"We are at the intermediary stage and fully engaged in the
process of dialogue with key interlocutors to come to a mutual and
joint agreement," said the sources. They said India had already
initiated talks with Russia, France and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The sources confirmed that Deputy Chairman of the Planning
Commission Jaswant Singh was scheduled to meet U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott in Frankfurt this week to
continue the dialogue between the two countries. 
</P>
