<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Poor in Jakarta Reaches 1.4 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of poor people in the
Indonesian capital of Jakarta is estimated to have risen to 1.4
million, or 14.7 percent of the city's 9.5 million population, The
Jakarta Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 1.4 million poor people come from 191,776 families, with
each family assumed to consist of seven family members, said
Rusmandesiar, head of the population section of the Central Bureau
of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the number of people living below the poverty line in
Jakarta was 497,000, or 5.6 percent of the city's total population
of 8.79 million at the time.
</P>
<P>
The number of poor in the capital dropped to 231,000 in 1996,
or 2.5 percent of the then population of 9.3 million.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the rise of poor people in the capital, Rusmandesiar
said it was caused mainly by the country's deteriorating economy.
Inflation was running high at above 40 percent in the first half
of this year and forecasts suggest the economy would contract by
15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
A free fall of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar has also
devastated per capita incomes and caused the poverty line to move
upwards, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Central Bureau of Statistics said the
number of poor people in Indonesia has increased from 22.5 million
in 1996 to 79.4 million now due to the monetary crisis gripping
the country since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The figure would increase to 95.8 million, or about 48 percent
of the country's total population of 202 million by the end of
this year as no economic recovery is in sight, the bureau said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
