<HEADLINE> Threatened Deer Species Saved in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The rare Sambar deer which three
years ago was on the brink of extinction has been successful bred
in Indonesia's East Kalimantan Province, local press reports said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The success of the deer breeding program is encouraging in view
of the fact the deer population in the province has come under
severe pressure from illegal hunting, the reports quoted the head
of the local husbandry office as saying.
</P>
<P>
The program began in 1991 with three pairs of deer and now
there are 94 deer roaming on a 1,000-hectare park, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Outside the park, deer of this species, which can weigh up to
200 kilograms, are prized by hunters for their meat," he said,
adding that around 5,000 deer are thought to be killed annually by
hunters. 
</P>
