<HEADLINE> Machine-Building Industry Retains Key Role in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- China's massive infrastructure
construction efforts and growing automobile production will
significantly increase the demand for machine tools and invigorate
the old machine-building industry, according to He Guangyuan,
former minister of the machine-building industry.
</P>
<P>
During a recent scientific manufacturing seminar in Wuhan, He,
who is currently president of the Chinese Machine-building
Engineering Society, still cited the loss-making machine-building
industry as one of the most vigorous growth points in China's
industrial sector, with an average annual growth rate of 14
percent over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
China's machinery exports yielded about 30 billion U.S. dollars
in foreign exchange revenues for 1997 and accounted for some 20
percent of total exports. China's output of power generating
equipment ranks the fourth in the world, with the output of
machine-tools holding a sixth place ranking.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, large projects, including power stations,
petrochemical plants, ports, transportation systems, steel and
automobile production create a massive demand for machinery and
equipment, he noted. China has more than 120 automotive
manufacturers and over 600 refitting factories.
</P>
<P>
The industry, which makes up 23 percent of the total national
industrial output value, has been honored as the core of Chinese
industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
