<HEADLINE> Early Results in Mexican Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican ruling party, the
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), has won the local
elections in the northern states of Chihuahua and Durango,
preliminary results from the weekend voting indicated on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition party, the Democratic Revolutionary
Party (PRD), claimed victory with its first-yet governorship in
the state of Zacatecas, the results revealed. With 60 percent of
the ballots counted, the PRD led with 42.5 percent of the vote
versus 36.6 percent for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral State Institute (IIE) in Chihuahua, said that the
PRI candidate for the state governor position, Patricio Martinez,
was leading with 48.7 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Ramon Galindo from the National Action Party (PAN) had 41
percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 2,860 polling stations counted, PRI had won 309,585
votes, PAN, 260,248 votes.
</P>
<P>
PAN had won in seven townships, and the PRD only one, Namiquipa.
</P>
<P>
In Juarez City, PAN collected 115,250 votes, while PRI garnered
110,228 votes.
</P>
<P>
The weekend elections were seen as a harbinger for seven more
governors' races this year and a crucial test for all three major
political parties as they jockey for position ahead of the year
2000 presidential contest, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
