<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Hosts World Health, Urban Environment Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Urban planners, more than 800 of
them from 50 countries, gathered here Monday to discuss health and
environmental issues arising from urban development.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the first of the kind, would focus on possible
solutions to these problems, so as to lay the ground work for a
program of action for future urban planning worldwide.
</P>
<P>
As shown by statistics, 50 percent of the world population
currently is living in urban areas. And the proportion is likely
to go up to 70 percent at the end of the coming 21st century.
</P>
<P>
By the year of 2015, at least 100 mega-cities are expected to
emerge, each home to the population ranging from 5 to 25 million.
</P>
<P>
Opened by Spanish Environment Minister Isabel Tocino, the
Madrid conference would address the urbanization-related issues
from technical, medical, social and government perspectives.
</P>
<P>
Director-General Federico Mayor of the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) joined
the opening session, together with Spanish Health Minister Jose
Manuel Romay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
