<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Individuals Embrace Legal Consultations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Legal consultation used to be
beyond the reach of ordinary Chinese, but is now becoming much
more common, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
By 1997, China had 11,000 individuals, privately-owned
industrial and commercial enterprises, and contractors who had
hired lawyers as legal consultants, according to statistics from
the Department of Lawyers Administration under the Ministry of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
These three categories make up the clients of China's "family
lawyers," or privately-hired lawyers.
</P>
<P>
These clients come from nearly every part of the country with
Central China's Hunan, Hubei and Henan provinces spearheading the
trend.
</P>
<P>
Though a tiny number compared with the country's huge
population, these 11,000 spell a significant improvement in
Chinese people's legal sense.
</P>
<P>
In China, family lawyers have only appeared in recent years as
the market economy has brought more complicated social
relationships.
</P>
<P>
"The extension of the legal system and the popularization of
laws have improved citizens' legal awareness," said Zhou
Yuansheng, the department's section chief. "They have learnt to
use laws to settle disputes and defend their legitimate rights."
</P>
<P>
China restored its lawyers' system in 1979. Nineteen years
later, the country has about 8,400 law firms with over 100,000
lawyers, according to ministry statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orban Elected New Hungarian Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Right-wing leader Viktor Orban was
sworn in as Hungary's new prime minister on Monday immediately
after being elected by a parliamentary vote.
</P>
<P>
Orban is expected to form an 18-member cabinet after President
Arpad Goencz approves his nominees.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year leader of the Federation of Young
Democrats-Hungarian Civic Party (Fidesz-MPP) won 222 votes from
the 386 legislators.
</P>
<P>
A total of 119 legislators voted against him, eight abstained
and 37 did not vote.
</P>
<P>
Fidesz-MPP won 148 seats in the 386-seat National Assembly
during legislative elections in May.
</P>
<P>
It has forged a coalition with the rural-based Independent
Smallholder's Party, with 48 seats, and the conservative Hungarian
Democratic Forum with 17 seats.
</P>
<P>
Born in Szekesfehervar, a city 50 kilometers southwest of
Budapest, Orban became a founding member of the Fidesz-MPP in 1988
at the age of 25.
</P>
<P>
He was elected into the National Assembly in 1990, rose to the
chair of the Fidesz-MPP in 1993 and became a parliamentary member
again in 1994, heading the commission for European integration
affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
