<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, July 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Monday he has
agreed to hold a summit meeting with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin in early September in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The White House issued a brief written statement saying Clinton
asked Vice President Al Gore to use his July 23-24 meetings in
Moscow with Russian officials to prepare the agenda for the
summit. (US-Russia-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Knesset (Parliament) Monday accepted the
policy statement made by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over
the peace talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The statement was passed in a vote of 43 to 42 after a heated
debate, in which the opposition attacked Netanyahu's policies in
dealing with the peace process. (Israel-Netanyahu-Parliament)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has warned
that the deteriorating situation in Kosovo could potentially
destabilize the entire Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
In a new report to the U.N. Security Council, which was
disclosed by the U.N. Department of Public Information on Monday,
Annan said a new outbreak of violence in Kosovo caused some 6,900
refugees to flee to Albania by the end of June. (UN-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Japan must "move aggressively and quickly" to
rehabilitate its banking sector for the sake of other crisis-hit
Asian economies, said Michel Camdessus, Managing Director of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Calling the recent fall of Japanese yen "a crisis with the
crisis," he said the new development could seriously jeopardize
the ongoing recovery of the economies that were hit first since
the Asian economic woes began a year ago. (UN-Asian Crisis-Impact)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- A United Nations economic survey has found that the
western economies have achieved dynamic growth in the first half
of 1998 despite a deepening economic crisis in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Economic developments in the western market economies were
generally positive in the first half of 1998, said the U.N.
Economic Commission for Europe (UN/ECE) in its Economic Survey of
Europe published here Tuesday. (UN-Western Economies) 
</P>
</TEXT>
