<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fishery Business On Northwestern Chinese Qinghai Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Fish like the rainbow trout, tilapia
mossambica and whitebait were practically unheard of in China's
Qinghai Province, but they have now become a regular feature on
the tables there, thanks to events of the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The growing business in this plateau area is a dramatic change,
local residents say, because the province now has 7 fishing bases
on 4,600 hectares of land, with 17 types of fish, and an annual
output of 10,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The province has used high-tech methods to raise aquatic
products, including a development project financed by the UN Food
and Agriculture Organization.
</P>
<P>
It also established a fingerling propagation center, and
produces two million carp fingerlings annually and is making an
effort to get a better breeding system for rainbow trout.
</P>
<P>
Fishery developers are making the most of local reservoirs, in
addition to ponds, to raise fish, as market demand is still on the
rise, an official of the provincial Aquatic Product Bureau
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
