<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Calls on Japan to Shore up Banking Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Japan must "move
aggressively and quickly" to rehabilitate its banking sector for
the sake of other crisis-hit Asian economies, said Michel
Camdessus, Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Calling the recent fall of Japanese yen "a crisis with the
crisis", he said the new development could seriously jeopardize the
ongoing recovery of the economies that were hit first since the
Asian economic woes began a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"It adds to the market instability that is again affecting
other countries within the region, as well as some countries,
including Russia, outside it," he told a U.N. Economic and Social
Council (ECOSOC) forum dealing with the impact of the Asian crisis
on world trade.
</P>
<P>
Turning to recent U.S.-Japan joint intervention to bail out
yen, Camdessus said it would be illusory to consider that only
interventions themselves can bring yen to the proper level.
</P>
<P>
"Interventions are only meaningful when they come in support
and as a harbinger of structural measures that are much more
fundamental which japan has begun to undertake," he said,
referring to reforms providing tax relief by the Japanese
Government.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said it is also vital that countries with balance of
payments surpluses recycle these surpluses in the form of "untied
loans" and humanitarian aid to countries in the process of
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
Creditors should grant generous terms for their loans and
should keep their markets open, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
