<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Survey Finds Western Economies Achieve Dynamic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations economic survey has
found that the western economies have achieved dynamic growth in
the first half of 1998 despite a deepening economic crisis in East
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Economic developments in the western market economies were
generally positive in the first half of 1998, said the U.N.
Economic Commission for Europe (UN/ECE) in its Economic Survey of
Europe published here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The expected negative effects of the east Asian crisis on net
exports have only gradually started to appear and so far they have
been offset by stronger domestic demand, the UN/ECE said.
</P>
<P>
In North America, the economic expansion has continued at a
high rate. In western Europe, the cyclical recovery has continued
at a moderate pace.
</P>
<P>
In East Asia, the survey said, the economic and social costs of
adjustment to be faced after the turbulence in the financial
markets have become more visible in 1998.
</P>
<P>
A significant deterioration of the economic situation in Japan,
which moved into deep recession, and the associated sharp
depreciation of the yen have seriously dampened prospects for
recovery in the region, according to the UN/ECE survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
