<HEADLINE> U.S. to Raise Funds for DPRK Oil Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States acknowledged
on Monday that it had not yet raised enough fund to supply the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) with heavy fuel
oil, but expressed confidence that the problem could be solved.
</P>
<P>
"We are sure we are going to be able to fulfil our side of
the bargain," State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1994 U.S.-DRPK agreement, the United States should
provide 500,000 metric tons of heavy fuel oil to DPRK every
year as it was to freeze its nuclear program in return for a new
light water reactor, to be built by a new consortium, the Korean
Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO).
</P>
<P>
The United States, South Korea, Japan and the European Union
are board members of KEDO.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin said so far this year KEDO had delivered only
about 152,000 metric tons of heavy fuel oil. By the end of the
month, that figure will have risen to 216,000, he said, meaning
284,000 tons will be needed in the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the administration was consulting with Congress
about extra funding for oil purchases. And he said the United
States will also help KEDO raise additional funds from other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Rubin indicated President Bill Clinton had expressed
readiness to use "certain provisions of U.S. law" to come up
with the extra funds. But he gave no details.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
