<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Foreign Minister Visits Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Foreign Minister Borys
Tarasyuk said here on Monday he will discuss trade and economic
cooperation with U.S. officials during his visit to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said at the National Press Club he will
also discuss Ukraine's efforts to join the European Union when he
meets Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation with the United States has been crucial in
consolidating Ukraine as a stable, democratic, viable partner and
ally of the United States," Tarasyuk said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that while the United States is Ukraine's
largest foreign investor, it would be unrealistic to say that
American investors have no problems in his country.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine recognizes the existence of disputes and is working to
settle them in a constructive and civilized manner," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine, the third largest recipient of U.S. assistance, has
recently been spared a substantial aid cut after making
significant progress in resolving complaints of U.S. investors
over corruption, red tape and other impediments to business.
</P>
<P>
Since gaining independence from the Soviet Union, foreign
businesses have invested about two billion U.S. dollars in
Ukraine, a figure described by State Department officials as
abysmally low when compared with the country's potential.
</P>
<P>
Tarasyuk is also scheduled to meet Defense Secretary William
Cohen and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of a Senate
Appropriations subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Ukraine's joining the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is not on the agenda of his visit.
</P>
<P>
"One may not exclude in principle Ukraine's joining ay security
institution, NATO included," he said, but adding that "proper
conditions must be prepared" for the process. "At this moment we
cannot say that these conditions are right in Ukraine."
</P>
<P>
"That is why the issue of Ukraine joining the alliance is not
on the agenda today," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
NATO has indicated that any European country, including
Ukraine, will be accepted if they meet criteria of NATO.
Russia strongly opposes Ukraine's joining the alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
