<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Move Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks rose sharply
Monday, with the S&AMP;P 500 being lifted to another record and the Dow
industrials pushing to the highest level since late May.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 66.51 points to 9,091.77,
increasing this year's gain to 15 percent. It is now just 120
points below May 13's record close of 9,211.84 and the blue-chip
barometer's highest finish since May 22.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index closed at a new high for the
fifth time in eight sessions. The NYSE composite index set a
closing record for the second session in a row after more than a
two-month drought.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 10.89 points to 1,157.31,
extending this year's gain to 19.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 15.43 to 1,909.43, about 8
points from April 22's record of 1,917.61. The technology-heavy
index slid 20 points on Thursday amid some profit-taking on its
11.6 percent surge of recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where its volume totaled 513.22 million
shares, almost even with Thursday's pre-holiday tally of 509.40
million. The NYSE composite index rose 5.02 to a record 590.82.
</P>
<P>
Smaller-company measures continued to lag the blue-chip advance,
and remained well below record terrain. The Russell 2000 rose 1.66
to 459.97, and the American Stock Exchange composite index rose
3.20 to 725.12.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
