<DOCNO> XIE19980707.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth of Developing Countries to Fall to 2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in
developing countries in 1998 is expected to be half of that in
1997, falling to almost two percent, Secretary-General of U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) Rubens Ricupero said
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Since the outbreak of the Asian economic crisis, the downward
revisions in gross domestic product (GDP) growth forecasts have
been more substantial for developing than for developed countries,
he told a U.N. Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) session.
</P>
<P>
Beginning Monday, the three-day forum with participation of
leaders of Breeton Woods institutions is dealing with the impact
of the Asian crisis on world trade.
</P>
<P>
"Given the bleak prospects for recovery in East Asia, we expect
the widening of the income gap between the North and the South to
continue," he said.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in many years, excluding China, growth in
the developing world will fall below that of the developed
world," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, developing countries are expected to be
affected more than the developed countries by negative trends in
the volume and export prices of their goods, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"The collapse of growth in East Asia has been the single most
important factor in the recent declines in the prices of many
commodities, including oil, agricultural raw materials and
metals.
</P>
<P>
"For some of these countries, up to a quarter of export
earnings may be lost," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to financial globalization, the UNCTAD chief said it
is much more difficult to manage integration into international
capital markets than it is to successfully insert oneself into the
international trading system.
</P>
<P>
"This is why one should avoid pushing or pressuring developing
countries into premature financial liberalization, thus denying
them the option to protect their economies from international
financial instability, and volative and speculative capital
flows," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
